# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: william-s-condon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autism diagnoses have risen since the 1990s, largely because of broader diagnostic criteria, greater awareness, and wider access to assessment.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Changing social demands may also play a role.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The World Health Organization estimates that about 1 in 100 children were diagnosed between 2012 and 2021, noting an increasing trend.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Surveillance studies suggest a similar share of the adult population would meet diagnostic criteria if formally assessed.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autism is highly heritable and involves many genes, while environmental factors appear to play a smaller, mainly prenatal role.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Boys are diagnosed several times more often than girls, with girls being better at hiding autistic traits.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Conditions such as anxiety, depression, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), epilepsy, as well as intellectual disability, are more common among autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people are also more likely to be a part of the LGBTQ community.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Certain savant abilities are also more common in autistic people than in other groups.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Several autism therapies aim to improve self-care, social, and language skills.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Reducing environmental and social barriers helps autistic people participate more fully in education, employment, and other aspects of life.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] No medication addresses the core features of autism, but some are used to help manage commonly co-occurring conditions, such as anxiety, depression, irritability, ADHD, and epilepsy.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The idea of autism as a disorder has been challenged by the neurodiversity framework, which frames autistic traits as a healthy variation of the human condition.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This perspective, promoted by the autism rights movement, has attracted increasing research attention, but is debated and remains controversial among autistic people, advocacy groups, healthcare providers, and charities.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autism is primarily characterized by differences and difficulties in social interaction and communication, alongside restricted or repetitive patterns of interests, activities, or behaviors (stimming), and, in many cases, distinctive reactions to sensory input.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The specific presentation varies widely.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] In most cases, signs of autism are first observable in infancy or early childhood and remain throughout life.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people may be significantly disabled in some respects, but average—or, in some cases, superior—in others.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people may have differences in social communication and interaction, which can lead to challenges in environments structured around non-autistic norms.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Diagnostic criteria for autism require difficulties across three social domains: social-emotional reciprocity, nonverbal communication, and developing and maintaining relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Common early signs of autism include little or no babbling in infancy.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Difficulties may also be apparent in traditional forms of reciprocal social interaction, such as games like peek-a-boo or pat-a-cake, as well as in shared attention to objects of interest; this may distinguish autistic from non-autistic infants.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This may present as social naïvety, lower-than-average intuitive perception of the meaning or utility of body language, social reciprocity, or social expectations, including the habitus, social cues, and certain aspects of sarcasm, which to some degree may be influenced by co-occurring alexithymia.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A 2019 meta-analysis found that alexithymia commonly co-occurs in autism (49.93%) and infrequently in neurotypicals (4.89%); the random effects risk ratio (6.50) was statistically significant (p<0.001).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Recent research has increasingly questioned these earlier interpretations, as the double empathy problem theory (2012) proposes that misunderstandings arise mutually between autistic and non-autistic people, rather than solely from autistic deficits in empathy or social cognition.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This perspective has contributed to a growing recognition that autistic behavior and communication may reflect different, rather than deficient, social behavior and communication styles.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic interests and conversational styles are often characterized by a strong focus on specific topics, a phenomenon known as monotropism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Differences in verbal communication often become noticeable in early childhood, as many autistic children develop language skills at an uneven pace.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Speech may emerge later than is typical or not at all (non-speaking autism), while reading ability may be present before school age (hyperlexia).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Infants may show delayed onset of babbling, atypical gestures, lower responsiveness, or vocal patterns that are less synchronized with caregivers.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] During the second and third years, autistic children may produce less frequent and less varied babbling, consonants, words, and word combinations, and may integrate gestures with speech less often.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] They are less likely to make requests or share experiences, and more likely to repeat others' words or phrases (echolalia).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] About 25–35% of autistic school-age children are non-speaking or minimally speaking.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The age at which speech develops and the complexity of early language development are significant predictors of verbal communication abilities in later life.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people often display atypical behaviors or differences in nonverbal communication.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Some may make infrequent eye contact, even when called by name, or avoid it altogether because they find it uncomfortable, distracting, or overstimulating.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Conversely, some autistic people make eye contact that others perceive as intense or unrelenting.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] They may recognize fewer emotions or interpret facial expressions differently, and may not respond with expressions expected by their non-autistic peers.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] They can also have difficulty inferring social context or subtext in conversation or text, resulting in different interpretations of meaning.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Speech characteristics such as volume, rhythm, and intonation (prosody) can vary, and atypical prosody is estimated to occur in at least half of autistic children.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Signs of autism in childhood include less apparent interest in other children or caregivers, possibly with more interest in objects.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Behaviors that may appear as indifference to non-autistic people often reflect autistic differences in recognizing others' personalities, perspectives, and interests.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Children on the autism spectrum are more likely than their non-autistic peers to be involved in bullying, most often as victims.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Among autistic people who seek friendships, reduced friendship quality and quantity are often associated with increased loneliness.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people also face greater challenges in developing romantic relationships than non-autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Over time, many autistic people learn to observe and form models of social patterns, and develop coping strategies, such as "masking".
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Masking is associated with poorer mental health outcomes as well as delayed diagnosis, which can limit access to appropriate supports.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The second core feature of autism is a pattern of restricted and repetitive behaviors, activities, and interests.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] To be diagnosed with autism under the DSM-5-TR, a person must exhibit at least two of the following behaviors: repetitive behaviors, resistance to change, focused interests and sensory reactivity.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It is increasingly argued that these characteristics should be accepted, which is supported by their recognized functions, such as self-regulation.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Focused interests can also provide personal fulfillment and contribute to the development of specialized knowledge.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A distinction should be made between these features and those of obsessive–compulsive disorder, which can co-occur with autism and involve compulsions or obsessions aimed at preventing feared outcomes.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Repetitive behaviors found in autism include rocking, hand flapping, finger flicking, head banging, and repeating phrases or sounds (including echolalia).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These behaviors may occur consistently or primarily when the person is stressed, anxious, or upset.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Other examples include playing with toys in ways others might consider limited or unusual (e.g., arranging toys in a row).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] In adults with autism, stimming is also used as a coping mechanism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Many adults learn to suppress (or "mask") these behaviors, which can increase their stress and anxiety.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people may have a strong preference for routine, such as performing daily tasks in a specific order or showing distress in response to changes others may consider minor.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] They may become distressed if their routine changes or is disrupted.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people may have an intense interest in a particular activity, topic, or hobby, often accompanied by sustained attention and deep knowledge; for example, a strong attachment to certain objects or frequent discussion of a certain topic.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Atypical responses may arise in autistic people in response to certain sensory input, such as aversion to specific sounds or textures, fascination with lights or movement, or apparent indifference to pain or temperature.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This is experienced by 90% of autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] They can be hyperactive or hypoactive in response to sensory input.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Some underreact to pain and temperature while others have a stronger reaction to it.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Self-harm occurs about three times more often in autistic people than in non-autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Behaviors can include head-banging, hand-biting, and skin-picking, and can lead to serious injury or, in rare cases, death.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Several explanations have been proposed for the development and persistence of self-harm among people with developmental conditions such as autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Communication difficulties may lead some autistic people to use self-injury to express needs, distress, or other feelings.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Self-harm may also help regulate sensory input or modulate pain perception, particularly for those with chronic discomfort or medical conditions.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Neurological factors are also under investigation, with atypical basal ganglia connectivity suggested as a potential biological predisposition in some autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Some autistic people "wander" off—a behavior known as *elopement*—and put themselves in danger.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] About half of families with autistic children report elopement.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The propensity for elopement increases with the severity of the autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Siblings unaffected by autism show much lower rates of elopement.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Drowning, a leading cause of death for autistic children, and traffic injuries are among the dangers associated with elopement.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Several non-diagnostic models have been used to describe challenges that autistic people face in their daily lives.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These concepts lack formal clinical criteria but are widely described by autistic people themselves.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic fatigue or burnout is a prolonged state of mental and physical exhaustion.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It is described as distinct from but similar to occupational burnout and is often linked to the pressure to hide autistic traits in social interactions.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The term "autistic burnout" was first used in 2008, with research into the phenomenon undertaken in the 2020s.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Several researchers have proposed characterizations of autistic burnout, but no consensus definition exists.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Depression can be misattributed to autistic burnout, as they have several overlapping criteria.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Reported coping strategies include reduced masking, increased stimming, engaging in special interests and familiar activities, and seeking stress relief.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Some affected people temporarily withdraw from social contact as a recovery strategy; while providing relief, interpersonal withdrawal can also result in loneliness and worsening mental health.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] There is limited data on professional interventions.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic inertia is a difficulty experienced among autistic people with initiating, transitioning between, or stopping activities or mental states.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It may manifest as a feeling of being "stuck": people find it challenging to begin a task, shift focus to a different activity, or disengage from an action, even when they want to.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A meltdown may occur if, upon processing large amounts of information, an autistic person experiences anxiety or feels overwhelmed.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Triggers may be sensory or social, and often include unpredictability, unmet basic needs, and emotional situations, which tend to accumulate.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A meltdown can be expressed audibly (e.g., screaming or crying) or physically.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The person often shows signs of distress beforehand, such as pacing, asking repetitive questions, trembling, or sweating.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] An autistic shutdown is similar, but inward; the person is often unable to speak or withdraws completely.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Meltdowns or shutdowns may be prevented by eliminating the distressing factors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] They may be ameliorated by avoiding further questions or pressure, showing the person that one is there to help, and allowing the person to calm down by leaving the situation or breathing slowly.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people often show an uneven or "spiky" cognitive profile, with relative strengths in some cognitive domains alongside difficulties in others.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The otherwise rare savant syndrome, characterized by an isolated skill in a narrow area, is more common among autistic people, but studies of its prevalence have found different results.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These special skills are related to prodigious memory.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Most common are splinter skills, such as memorization of sports trivia or historical facts.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Research has also reported enhanced performance by autistic participants on certain perceptual and attentional tasks.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people may exhibit traits or characteristics that are not part of the formal diagnostic criteria but can nonetheless affect their personal well-being or family dynamics.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The exact causes of autism are unknown, with genetics likely being the largest contributing factor.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It was long presumed a single cause at the genetic, cognitive, and neural levels underpinned the social and non-social features, but autism is increasingly thought to be a complex condition with distinct, often co-occurring, causes for its core aspects.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It is unlikely that autism has a single cause; research has identified many factors as potential contributors, including genetics, prenatal and perinatal (shortly after birth) history, neuroanatomical anomalies, changing social demands in the workplace or in school, and environmental influences.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It is possible to identify general factors but difficult to determine specific ones.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Research into causes is complex due to challenges in identifying distinct biological subgroups in the autistic population.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autism has a strong genetic basis, but the genetics of autism are complex and it is unclear whether autism is explained more by rare mutations with major effects or by rare multi-gene interactions of common genetic variants.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Twin studies indicate that autism is highly heritable, with genetic factors explaining most of the risk and shared environmental effects playing a minor role.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Numerous genes have been found to be associated with autism, with most loci individually explaining less than 1% of autism cases and having only small effects.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] While these genetic variants are associated with a higher likelihood of being autistic, they do not individually determine whether someone will be autistic.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Complexity arises from interactions among multiple genes, the environment, and heritable epigenetic factors (which influence gene expression without changing DNA sequence).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Typically, autism is not traceable to a single-gene (Mendelian) mutation or chromosome anomaly, and no known genetic syndrome selectively causes autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] If autism is one characteristic of a broader medical condition, such as fragile X syndrome, it is called syndromic autism, as opposed to non-syndromic or idiopathic autism, which is typically polygenic without a known cause.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Syndromic autism is present in approximately 25% of autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Research has suggested that autistic people with intellectual disability tend to have rarer, more impactful, genetic mutations than those found in people diagnosed solely with autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A number of genetic syndromes causing intellectual disability may also co-occur with autism, including fragile X, Down, Prader–Willi, Angelman, Williams syndrome, and SYNGAP1-related intellectual disability.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Research suggests that autism is associated with genes that influence neural development and connectivity.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These are involved in key neuronal processes such as protein synthesis, synaptic activity, cell adhesion, and the formation and remodeling of synapses, as well as the regulation of excitatory and inhibitory neurotransmission.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Genes associated with variation in the mTOR signaling pathway, which is involved in cell growth and survival, are also under investigation.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Some hypotheses in evolutionary psychiatry suggest that autism-associated genes may persist because of proposed links to traits such as intelligence, systematizing abilities, or innovation.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] If parents have one autistic child, the chance of having a second autistic child ranges from 7% to 20%.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Though autism is highly heritable, many autistic people have only non-autistic family members.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] In some cases, this may be explained by de novo structural variations—such as deletions, duplications, or inversions—that arise spontaneously during meiosis and are not present in the parents' genomes.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The likelihood of being autistic is greater with older fathers than with older mothers; two potential explanations are the known increase in the number of mutations in older sperm and the hypothesis that men marry later if they carry a genetic predisposition and show some signs of autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Research on the evolutionary advantages of autism and associated genes has suggested that autistic people may have contributed uniquely to human development, particularly in technological innovation (such as tool-making) and in detailed observation and analysis of the natural environment.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Systematic reviews emphasize that these ideas remain speculative and that no single evolutionary explanation has been established.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Recent studies show that social diffusion can contribute to increased rates of autism diagnosis.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Proximity for children that have the same severity of autism can increase prevalence due to increased expression of symptoms of autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This is seen in children with high-functioning autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Various theoretical frameworks attempt to integrate underlying genetic and environmental causes with observed neurobiological findings and behavioral traits.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Beyond models of causation and brain function, cognitive theories have been developed to explain patterns of information processing common in autistic people, to better understand the autistic phenotype.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] While these cognitive accounts describe how autistic traits may manifest, they are generally viewed as explanations of the behavioral and cognitive consequences of the underlying neurobiological development rather than primary causes themselves.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Certain factors during pregnancy and birth may increase the likelihood of autism, although no single factor is conclusive and study results are often inconsistent.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These factors include advanced parental age, maternal health conditions (e.g., gestational diabetes, infections such as rubella, inflammation), exposure to certain medications (e.g., valproate), and some environmental exposures like significant air pollution during pregnancy.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] While many environmental factors have been investigated, few have established links, and some prominent claims (e.g., vaccines or parenting styles) have been disproven.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Work on autism in the mid-20th century proposed the "frigid mother" or refrigerator mother hypothesis, according to which poor parenting or lack of emotional support from parents leads to autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] When it was proposed, the hypothesis contributed to considerable media attention about autism, which had previously been mostly ignored.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The hypothesis has since fallen out of favor, and has not garnered support when studied.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] But the blame placed on parents of children on the autism spectrum, especially mothers, has contributed to substantial stigma.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Early social experiences, such as caregiver interactions or deprivation, may shape the development of autism, potentially via gene–environment correlations, and are distinct from the discredited refrigerator mother hypothesis.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Parents may first become aware of autistic characteristics in their child around the time of a routine vaccination.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This has led to theories – subsequently disproven – blaming vaccine "overload", the vaccine preservative thiomersal, or the MMR vaccine for causing autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] In 1998, British physician Andrew Wakefield led a fraudulent, litigation-funded study that suggested that the MMR vaccine may cause autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] His co-authors have since recanted the claims made in the study.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Wakefield was struck off the British medical register for "serious professional misconduct" after determination that his involvement in the study amounted to fraud, leading to the loss of his right to practice medicine.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Two versions of the vaccine causation hypothesis were that autism results from brain damage caused by either the MMR vaccine itself, or by mercury used as a vaccine preservative.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] No convincing scientific evidence supports these claims.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] They are biologically implausible, and further evidence continues to refute them, including the observation that the rate of autism continues to climb despite elimination of thimerosal from most routine vaccines given to children from birth to 6 years of age.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A 2014 meta-analysis examined ten major studies on autism and vaccines involving 1.25 million children worldwide; it concluded that neither the vaccine preservative thimerosal (mercury), nor the MMR vaccine, which has never contained thimerosal, lead to autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Despite this, misplaced parental concern has led to lower rates of childhood immunizations, outbreaks of previously controlled childhood diseases in some countries, and the preventable deaths of several children.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Anti-vaccine activists have spread false claims about the absence of autism in North America's Amish population due to lower vaccination rates.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A 2010 study revealed that autism is present in 1 out of every 271 Amish children.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The mechanisms of autism are the molecular and cellular processes believed to cause or contribute to the symptoms of autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Multiple processes are hypothesized to explain different autistic features.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These hypotheses include defects in synapse structure and function, reduced synaptic plasticity, disrupted neural circuit function, gut–brain axis dyshomeostasis, neuroinflammation, and altered brain structure or connectivity.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autism symptoms stem from maturation-related changes in brain systems.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The mechanisms of autism are divided into two main areas: pathophysiology of brain structures and processes, and neuropsychological linkages between brain structures and behaviours, with multiple pathophysiologies linked to various autism behaviours.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Evidence suggests gut–brain axis abnormalities may contribute to autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Studies propose that immune, gastrointestinal inflammation, autonomic nervous system dysfunction, gut microbiota alterations, and dietary metabolites may contribute to brain neuroinflammation and dysfunction.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Additionally, enteric nervous system abnormalities could play a role in neurological disorders by allowing disease pathways from the gut to impact the brain.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Synaptic dysfunction also appears to be implicated in autism, with some mutations disrupting synaptic pathways involving cell adhesion.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Evidence points to teratogens affecting the early developmental stages, suggesting autism arises very early, possibly within the first eight weeks after conception.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Neuroanatomical studies support that autism may involve abnormal neuronal growth and pruning, leading to brain enlargement in some areas and reduction in others.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Functional neuroimaging studies show reduced activation in somatosensory cortices during theory of mind tasks in autistic individuals and highlight potential imbalances in neurotransmitters like glutamate and Γ-aminobutyric acid that may underlie autism's behavioural manifestations.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The DSM-5 and ICD-11 are the two main frameworks for classification of mental disorders in use today.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autism spectrum disorder is classified in both as a neurodevelopmental disorder, with its definition encompassing a spectrum of highly varied presentations.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The spectrum concept signals diversity rather than a simple range from mild to severe.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Before the DSM-5 (2013) and ICD-11/ICD-11 CDDR (2019/2024), autism fell within a broader pervasive developmental disorder category that included labels such as Asperger syndrome and classic autism (also called childhood autism or Kanner syndrome).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Because these diagnoses overlapped, the manuals unified them under "autism spectrum disorder" (ASD).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Since 1980, the committees behind both manuals have aimed for greater convergence, incorporating biological research while keeping behavior-based criteria.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] ICD-11 instead records whether the person has co-occurring intellectual disability or language impairment.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Some researchers have questioned whether existing criteria capture the full phenomenon, prompting proposals for prototype descriptions, transdiagnostic biological markers, or distinctions between common behavioral traits and rarer genetic or environmental factors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The American Psychiatric Association's *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition, Text Revision* (DSM-5-TR), released in 2022, is the latest version.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Its fifth edition—DSM-5, released in 2013—was the first to define ASD as a single diagnosis, combining the previously distinct diagnoses of classic autism, Asperger syndrome, childhood disintegrative disorder, and pervasive developmental disorder not otherwise specified (PDD-NOS).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The DSM-5 and DSM-5-TR adopt a dimensional approach, with one diagnostic category for disorders that fall under the autism spectrum umbrella.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The two core symptom domains are (a) social communication and (b) restricted, repetitive behaviors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Clinicians may specify separate severity levels for each domain based on the degree to which symptoms affect daily functioning, rather than providing a single overall severity rating.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Before the fifth edition, the DSM separated social deficits and communication deficits into two domains.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The DSM-5 also revised the onset criteria to specify that symptoms appear in the early developmental period, noting that symptoms may manifest later when social demands exceed capabilities; the previous edition had required onset before age three.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The World Health Organization's International Classification of Diseases (11th revision), ICD-11, was released in 2018 and came into full effect in 2022.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] About half of parents of children with ASD notice their child's atypical behaviors by age 18 months, and about four-fifths notice by age 24 months.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] If a child does not meet any of the following milestones, it "is an absolute indication to proceed with further evaluations.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The Japanese practice is to screen all children for ASD at 18 and 24 months, using autism-specific formal screening tests.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] In contrast, in the UK, children whose families or doctors recognize possible signs of autism are screened.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It is not known which approach is more effective.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The UK National Screening Committee does not recommend universal ASD screening in young children.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Their main concerns includes higher chances of misdiagnosis at younger ages and lack of evidence of effectiveness of early interventions.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] There is no consensus between professional and expert bodies in the US on screening for autism in children younger than 3 years.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It may be more accurate to precede these tests with a broadband screener that does not distinguish ASD from other developmental disorders.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Screening tools designed for one culture's norms for behaviors like eye contact may be inappropriate for a different culture.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Although genetic screening for autism is generally still impractical, it can be considered in some cases, such as children with neurological symptoms and dysmorphic features.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] From the perspective of neurodiversity, "curing" or otherwise treating autism may not be an appropriate goal.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Interventions targeting specific challenges or co-occurring conditions associated with autism are widely regarded as important.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Perspectives on the goals of these interventions vary: the medical model of disability often focuses on addressing core characteristics such as social communication difficulties and restricted/repetitive behaviors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The neurodiversity movement supports interventions aimed at enhancing functional communication (spoken or non-spoken), managing related issues like anxiety or inertia, or addressing behaviors considered harmful, rather than seeking to alter core autistic features.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Studies of interventions have methodological problems that prevent definitive conclusions about efficacy, but the development of evidence-based interventions has advanced.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Several therapies can help autistic children, and they are typically tailored to the child's needs.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The main goals of therapy are to lessen associated difficulties and family distress, and to increase quality of life and functional independence.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] In general, higher IQs correlate with higher responsiveness to interventions and larger intervention outcomes.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Behavioral, psychological, educational, and skill-building interventions may be used to help autistic people learn skills for living independently, as well as other social, communication, and language skills.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Therapy also aims to reduce behaviors perceived as inappropriate and to build upon strengths.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Medications have not been found to reduce autism's core features, but may be used for associated difficulties, such as irritability or inattention.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Certain interventions, such as intensive, sustained special education, remedial education programs, and behavior therapy, are considered beneficial early in life for autistic children to acquire self-care, social, and job skills.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Available approaches include applied behavior analysis, developmental models, structured teaching, speech and language therapy, cognitive behavioral therapy, social skills therapy, and occupational therapy.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These interventions may either target autistic features comprehensively or focus on a specific area of difficulty.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Applied behavior analysis (ABA) is a behavioral therapy that aims to teach autistic children certain social and other behaviors by prompting using rewards and reinforcement learning.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This includes learning fine and gross motor and language skills through play, expressive labeling, and requesting.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] It also seeks to reduce aggressive and self-injurious behavior by assessing its environmental causes and reinforcing replacement behaviors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Early, intensive ABA therapy has demonstrated effectiveness in enhancing preschool children's language skills, adaptive functioning, and intellectual performance.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Another review reported a lack of adverse event monitoring, although such adverse effects may be common.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Interventions for early childhood may be based on different theoretical frameworks, such as ABA (with its structured and naturalistic approaches) and Developmental Social Pragmatic (DSP) models.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Sandoval-Norton et al. describe it as unethical and argue that it has unintended consequences, such as prompt dependency, susceptibility to psychological abuse, and overemphasis on compliance, which can create challenges in the transition to adulthood.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Increasingly, ABA is also criticized for trying to reduce or eliminate autistic behaviors to make children appear less autistic, rather than respecting neurodiversity.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A problem with unreported conflicts of interest in ABA research has been described, with potential effects on the quality of evidence.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] In response, some ABA advocates suggest that instead of discontinuing the therapy, efforts should focus on increasing protections and ethical compliance.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A related type of intervention is parent training models.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These teach parents to implement various ABA and DSP techniques themselves.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Several parent-mediated behavioral therapies target social communication difficulties, while their effect on restricted and repetitive behaviors (RRBs) is uncertain.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Similarly, teacher-implemented interventions that combine naturalistic ABA with a developmental social pragmatic approach have been associated with effects on young children's social-communication behaviors, although there is limited evidence regarding effects on broader autistic characteristics.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Inclusive education models strive to support autistic students in mainstream educational settings, moving away from segregated special education environments toward participation alongside their peers.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Despite these efforts, autistic students can face significant barriers, sometimes leading to trauma or emotionally-based school non-attendance.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] This avoidance is often rooted in overwhelming sensory environments, social anxieties, communication breakdowns, bullying, or lack of adequate support and understanding, rather than defiance.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Central to successful inclusion is the application of frameworks like Universal Design for Learning (UDL), which proactively designs curricula and learning environments to be accessible and engaging for all students, including those who are autistic.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] UDL principles accommodate varied learning styles, sensory sensitivities, and communication preferences often present in autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The SPACE framework (sensory, predictability, acceptance, communication, empathy) developed by Doherty et al., primarily for healthcare settings, offers a lens for identifying and addressing common environmental barriers that can contribute to distress and avoidance behaviors for autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Accommodations may include providing quiet spaces as a retreat for people feeling overwhelmed.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic students may also need help initiating and maintaining social relationships with their peers if they wish to do so.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Especially in higher education, some autistic students may need help with executive functioning, e.g., managing their own work, and the ability to initiate and complete tasks.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Transitioning to adulthood, autistic people often encounter substantial barriers to securing and maintaining meaningful employment, leading to high rates of unemployment and underemployment compared to the general population.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Challenges can include navigating traditional interview processes, difficulties with unspoken social rules in the workplace, sensory sensitivities to office environments (e.g., lighting, noise), and needs for clear, direct communication and structured tasks.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Effective workplace inclusion involves implementing reasonable adjustments such as flexible working hours or locations, providing noise-canceling headphones, staff training, and mentorship programs.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Working from home can help to avoid overwhelming sensory or social situations, even if this means losing desirable social contact.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autism-friendly workplaces not only allow autistic employees to utilize their unique skills and perspectives but also benefit employers through increased innovation, problem-solving capabilities, and employee loyalty.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic people may be prescribed medication to manage specific co-occurring conditions or behaviors, such as ADHD, anxiety, aggression, or self-injurious behaviors, particularly when non-pharmacological interventions alone have been insufficient.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Medications are not routinely recommended for autism's core features, such as social and communication difficulties or restricted and repetitive behaviors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] More than half of autistic children in the United States are prescribed psychoactive drugs or anticonvulsants.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Commonly used drug classes include antidepressants, stimulants, and antipsychotics.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Among antipsychotics, risperidone and aripiprazole are the only medications approved by the U.S.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Food and Drug Administration specifically for reducing irritability, aggression, and self-injurious behaviors in autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] These drugs can have significant side effects and responses to them may vary.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The UK's National Health Service cautions against the overprescription of antipsychotics and recommends their use only for specific indications, at the lowest effective dose and for the shortest duration necessary.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Some research suggests that risperidone and aripiprazole may also reduce restricted and repetitive behaviors, such as hand-flapping or body-rocking.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The evidence supporting this use has limitations, including study size and scope, alongside concerns about adverse effects.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] A meta-analysis found no significant efficacy of these antipsychotics or SSRI antidepressants in reducing these behaviors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Stimulant medications like methylphenidate may reduce inattention or hyperactivity in some autistic children, particularly when ADHD is also present.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] But methylphenidate's efficacy is lower in autistic people with ADHD compared to non-autistic people with ADHD, and side effects are more common.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Alternative therapies have been researched and implemented, and many have resulted in harm to autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] For example, chelation therapy is not recommended as a treatment for autism, with risks outweighing potential benefits.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Reports of death from botched chelation therapy as treatment for autism have been documented.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Medical authorities have condemned bleach-based approaches, such as chlorine dioxide solutions marketed as Miracle Mineral Solution, as dangerous and ineffective.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] The British NHS also warns against CEASE therapy, which rejects vaccinations and recommends potentially harmful amounts of dietary supplements.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] There is also no evidence for the efficacy of hyperbaric oxygen therapy and its use is not recommended.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Although sometimes used for autistic people, no reliable evidence indicates a gluten- and casein-free diet as a standard intervention.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Autistic children's preference for unconventional foods as well as gastrointestinal problems and lack of exercise can lead to reduction in bone cortical thickness, and this risk is greater in those on casein-free diets, as a consequence of the low intake of calcium and vitamin D.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Interventions for autistic adults have limited evidence; cognitive behavioral approaches and mindfulness are considered promising.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Music therapy for autistic people likely improves overall autism severity, global functioning, and quality of life, but evidence is unclear for social and communication skills.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Animal-assisted activities and therapies show promise in improving social communication, irritability, hyperactivity, and word usage in autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Families who care for an autistic child often experience greater stress.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Parents may struggle to understand their child and to find appropriate care options.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Affiliate stigma can also reduce quality of life, where negative attitudes toward the autistic child are extended to those close to them.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p01] Family members who are themselves autistic may be better able to understand the autistic child.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The prognosis after diagnosis of autism in childhood is poorly understood.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Some core diagnostic symptoms, including restricted and repetitive behaviors, are stable, but some gradual symptom changes occur.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Among children diagnosed before age 6, about 9 in 10 continue to meet diagnostic criteria one year later.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Some report that those with limited support needs are likely to have lessened autistic features over time, while others argue that this perception is likely due to masking—hiding autistic characteristics to avoid stigma.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Long-term outcomes vary, in part due to variability in presentation between individuals and across affected domains.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Autistic adults are more likely to be unemployed and have greater mental health service needs than the general population.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] About 85% of autistic people need support with independent living in adulthood.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Factors such as developing spoken language before age six, having an IQ above 50, and possessing marketable skills are associated with higher likelihood of independent living in adulthood.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Mortality among autistic people is approximately twice that of the general population, particularly among those with co-occurring neurologic or psychiatric disorders.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Risk factors for self-harm and suicidality include circumstances that could affect anyone but are more common among autistic people, such as mental health problems (e.g., anxiety disorder) and social problems (e.g., unemployment and social isolation).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] In addition, there are autism-specific factors, such as exhausting attempts to behave like a non-autistic person to avoid stigma and negative reactions of society towards autistic people (masking).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Autistic people are also at significantly increased risk of victimization, including bullying, sexual assault, and other forms of criminal abuse.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] A 2019 meta-analysis found autistic people to be four times more likely to have depression than non-autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Rates of suicidality vary significantly depending upon what is being measured.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] This is partly because questionnaires developed for non-autistic subjects are not always valid for autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] As of 2023, the Suicidal Behaviours Questionnaire–Autism Spectrum Conditions (SBQ-ASC) is the only test validated for autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] According to some estimates, about a quarter of autistic youth and a third of all autistic people have experienced suicidal ideation at some point.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Autistic people are about three times as likely as non-autistic people to make a suicide attempt.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Almost 10% of autistic youth and 15% to 25% of autistic adults have attempted suicide.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Rates of suicide attempts and suicidal ideation are the same for people formally diagnosed with autism and people who have typical intelligence and are believed to be autistic but have not been diagnosed.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The suicide risk is higher for autistic people who are not cisgender males and do not have intellectual disabilities.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Most professionals believe that race, ethnicity, and socioeconomic background have limited effect on the occurrence of autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Research indicates that autistic people are significantly more likely to be LGBTQ than the general population.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Autistic people are also significantly more likely to be non-theistic or non-religious.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Several conditions can co-occur with autism at a higher rate than in the rest of the population.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] This may be referred to as comorbidity, and may increase with age, causing difficulties for youth on the autism spectrum, and can make interventions and therapies more challenging.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Features of autism and other diagnoses often overlap, and autism's characteristics can make traditional diagnostic procedures more difficult.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] This is sometimes known as diagnostic overshadowing.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The World Health Organization notes that reports on prevalence vary widely.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] It estimates that about 1 in 127 children were autistic between 2012 and 2021 with a trend of increasing prevalence over time.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] This may reflect an underestimate of prevalence in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Surveillance studies in community samples of adults suggest a similar share of the adult population would meet diagnostic criteria if formally assessed.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The number of people diagnosed has increased since the 1990s, likely due to a combination of increased recognition of autism, better availability of diagnosis, and changes to the diagnostic criteria.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The increase in autism is largely attributable to changes in diagnostic practices, referral patterns, availability of services, age at diagnosis, and public awareness, particularly among women, though other unidentified environmental factors may exist.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The Centers for Disease Control's Autism and Developmental Disabilities Monitoring Network reported that approximately 1 in 31 children in the United States is diagnosed with autism, based on data collected in 2022.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] For 2016 data, the estimate was 1 in 54, compared to 1 in 68 in 2010 and 1 in 150 in 2000.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Diagnostic criteria for autism have changed significantly since the 1980s; for example, U.S. special-education autism classification was introduced in 1994.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Males are about three times more likely to be diagnosed with autism than females.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Several theories about the higher prevalence in males have been investigated.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Prevalence differences may be mainly due to a result of differences in expression of characteristics between males and females, with autistic women and girls showing less atypical behaviors and therefore being less likely to be diagnosed with autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The history of autism encompasses various conceptual and treatment approaches, with the understanding of autism having been shaped by cultural, scientific, and societal factors.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Pathologized or viewed as beneficial as part of neurodiversity, autism has been subject to various treatments.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Progress in scientific understanding of autism has contributed to both treatment and perceptions of autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] In 1911, Swiss psychiatrist Paul Eugen Bleuler coined the German term *Autismus* to characterize the social withdrawal he observed in people with schizophrenia.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Rendered in English as *autism*, the term derives from the Greek word autos ("self").
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Bleuler used the term for a symptom of adult schizophrenia: a person's retreat from reality into their own subjective world.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] He also mentioned "autistic thinking" as a fleeting, illogical thought process everyone experiences.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] In the mid-1920s, German psychiatrist Fritz Künkel categorized over 100 schizophrenic patients into four groups, one of which he labeled "autistic", highlighting disturbances in emotional life.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] In 1926, building on his work and Bleuler's, Grunya Sukhareva published an article about six boys who were musically gifted and had a tendency toward abstract thinking.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] She called their affects "flattened" and their tendency to avoid other children an "autistic attitude".
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Scholars have credited Sukhareva with making observations that closely mirror ASD as described by the DSM-5 and ICD-11.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Her work expanded on the definition throughout her career while making great strides in differentiating ASD and schizophrenia nearly 30 years before the establishment of separate classifications for these diagnoses with the 1980 publication of the DSM-III.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The autistic rights and neurodiversity movements argue autism should be accepted as a difference to be accommodated instead of cured, although a minority of autistic people might still accept a cure.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Social-science scholars study autistic people in hopes of learning more about "autism as a culture, transcultural comparisons ... and research on social movements".
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Events related to autism include World Autism Awareness Day, Autism Sunday, Autistic Pride Day, Autreat, and others.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Focused interests are commonly found in autistic people and can include activism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Environmental activist Greta Thunberg has spoken favorably about her autism diagnosis, saying that autism can be a source of life purpose, as well as the basis of careers, hobbies, and friendships.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] In Sweden, people with an autism diagnosis are required to provide additional proof of suitability to apply for a driver's license and may face barriers to entering military service.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] In the United Kingdom, an autistic police officer was rejected from firearms training, which a tribunal later ruled was illegal discrimination.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] In the United States, autism is generally a "disqualifying condition" for joining the military, but autistic people can apply for a medical waiver.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Discrimination against autistic people occurs in various forms, both directly and indirectly, in a variety of settings, professional, educational, or clinical.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Such discrimination is often initiated after other people identify the autistic person as different from themselves, which may occur very quickly.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] This discrimination sometimes leads to violence, assault, or social exclusion.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Various legal limitations on people with an autism diagnosis have also been considered discriminatory.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Some autistic people and affiliated researchers have advocated a shift in attitudes toward the view that autism is a difference, rather than a disease that ought to be treated or cured.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Critics have bemoaned the entrenchment of some of these groups' opinions, and that they speak to a select group of autistic people with limited difficulties.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Clinical and policy guidance in Australia, the United States, and the United Kingdom now promote neurodiversity-affirming language—for example, using "characteristics" instead of "symptoms" and avoiding words such as "cure".
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The neurodiversity movement and the autism rights movement are social movements within the context of disability rights, emphasizing the concept of neurodiversity, according to which autism is a result of healthy and valuable variations in the human brain rather than a disorder to be cured.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The autism rights movement advocates including greater acceptance of autistic behaviors, therapies that focus on coping skills rather than imitating the behaviors of non-autistic people, and the recognition of the autistic community as a minority group.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Autism rights or neurodiversity advocates believe the autism spectrum is genetic and should be accepted as a healthy variation in the human genome.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] A common argument against neurodiversity activists is that most have relatively few support needs or are self-diagnosed, and do not represent the views of autistic people with more support needs.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] It has been argued that only autistic people with lower support needs should be included under the neurodiversity banner, as autism with high support needs "may rightfully be viewed as a disability".
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The concept of neurodiversity is contentious in autism advocacy and research groups and has led to infighting.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Many autistic teenagers and adults struggle to learn to drive a car.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] By age 21, about 20% of autistic people in the US have a driver's license, compared to more than 60% of non-autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] They are less likely to start learning, likely to do it later than non-autistic peers, and less likely to proceed to the next stage.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] The differences are due to the characteristics of autism such as being slower to recognize pedestrians, having a slower reaction time, worse executive function, worse motor coordination, and poorer situational awareness (e.g., remembering that another vehicle is in their blind spot).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Parents' reactions to having their children diagnosed with autism vary.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] A study in Spain found that children diagnosed with autism and their parents faced stigma and societal challenges.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Stigma is created by societal standards that influence how parents think of autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Cultural values can influence how a parent feels; many feel defeated because they think they failed as a parent.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Spain has early intervention programs to help parents adapt to their children's diagnoses.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Stigma causes many parents to hide their children's condition, so their experiences are minimized or denied.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Since the 1990s, the number of people without co-occurring intellectual disability who are diagnosed with autism (including Asperger's syndrome and ASD) has increased.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Some autistic adults of average or above-average intelligence were not diagnosed in childhood because the condition was less well-understood.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Diagnosis in adulthood can have effects very different from those experienced by people diagnosed in childhood.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] A late diagnosis produces an emotional reaction and a phase of readjustment.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Late-diagnosed adults often report a history of being treated for anxiety and depression.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] Many report lifelong feelings of isolation and alienation.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-p02] After a period of readjustment, a late diagnosis is often viewed favorably, allowing previously unidentified needs to be met and support and accommodations to be requested.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] The **Autism Society of America** (**ASA**) is an American non-profit organization whose stated goal is "to improve the lives of all affected by autism." It was founded in 1965 by Bernard Rimland together with Ruth C.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Sullivan and a small group of other parents of autistic children.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Its original name was the **National Society for Autistic Children**; the name was changed to emphasize that autistic children grow up.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] In 1998, anti-vaccine activist Andrew Wakefield released a fraudulent study that falsely linked the MMR vaccine to autism (which was formally retracted by its publisher in 2010).
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Subsequent to its release, other scientifically unsupported theories (including "vaccine overload" and the bodies of autistic children being unable to eliminate thiomersal) increased in popularity.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] In 2016, Adams used his position as president of the Autism Society of Greater Phoenix to promote the release of Wakefield's anti-vaccination film, *Vaxxed,* and told the *Phoenix New Times* that he believed vaccines could cause autism in rare cases.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] As of 2025, Adams still sits on the chapter's board of directors and serves as a scientific advisor to the Rimland-founded Autism Research Institute.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Granpeesheh and Jepson were openly associated with the Wakefield-founded Thoughtful House Center for Children at the time they appeared at various ASA annual conferences in the mid- to late 2000s, and Granpeesheh appeared in *Vaxxed* in 2016.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Granpeesheh last sat on the ASA's national board of directors in 2009, and she and Herbert were most recently credited as advisors to the ASA in its 2021 annual report.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] In 2003, while serving on the ASA's national board of directors, Shore told *USA Today* that vaccines and thiomersal were potential catalysts for autism and that he believed autistic traits closely resembled the symptoms of mercury poisoning.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] The ASA platformed Wakefield, himself, at its 2007 annual conference.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Secretary of Health and Human Services and anti-vaccine activist Robert F.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] The ASA and its state and regional chapters have historically utilized controversial puzzle-piece imagery in their branding, including a trademarked puzzle-piece ribbon (introduced in 1999) and a graphic of a boy's head interwoven with puzzle pieces.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Some critics and researchers claim these types of symbols stigmatize autistic people because they portray them as incomplete, mysterious or a problem in need of fixing and evoke brokenness and bafflement.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Bernard Rimland (November 15, 1928 – November 21, 2006) was an American research psychologist, writer, lecturer, and influential person in the field of developmental disorders who is known for promoting autism-related pseudoscience.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] In 1964, Bernard Rimland wrote a book, *Infantile Autism*, that convinced others working in the field that autism is a physiological disorder, not a mental or emotional problem.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Rimland was a founder of the ASA in 1965, but left to create the Autism Research Institute in 1967.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] He later promoted several theories, which have since been disproven, about the causes and treatment of autism, including vaccine denial, facilitated communication, chelation therapy, and claims of a link between secretin and autism.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Rimland eventually returned to ASA leadership, last serving as an honorary member of the organization's board of directors the year he died.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Sullivan (April 20, 1924 – September 16, 2021) was an American organizer and advocate for the education of autistic people.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Sullivan was a founder and the first president of the ASA, but later left to start the Autism Services Center in Huntington, West Virginia.
[src:william-s-condon/autism-society-of-america] Sullivan eventually returned to ASA leadership, last serving as an honorary member of the organization's board of directors in 2008.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In social psychology, an **interpersonal relation** (or **interpersonal relationship**) describes a social association, connection, or affiliation between two or more people.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] It overlaps significantly with the concept of social relations, which are the fundamental unit of analysis within the social sciences.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Relations vary in degrees of intimacy, self-disclosure, duration, reciprocity, and power distribution.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The main themes or trends of the interpersonal relations are: family, kinship, friendship, love, marriage, business, employment, clubs, neighborhoods, ethical values, support, and solidarity.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Interpersonal relations may be regulated by law, custom, or mutual agreement, and form the basis of social groups and societies.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] They appear when people communicate or act with each other within specific social contexts, and they thrive on equitable and reciprocal compromises.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Interdisciplinary analysis of relationships draws heavily upon the other social sciences, including, but not limited to: anthropology, communication, cultural studies, economics, linguistics, mathematics, political science, social work, and sociology.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This scientific analysis had evolved during the 1990s and has become "relationship science", through the research done by Ellen Berscheid and Elaine Hatfield.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This interdisciplinary science attempts to provide evidence-based conclusions through the use of data analysis.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Friendships are non-sexual, non-romantic interpersonal relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Social relations can be homosocial such as female bonding and male bonding or heterosocial such as cross-sex friendship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In some countries a reduction of friendships is observed, also called friendship recession or loneliness epidemic.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] An intimate relationship is an interpersonal relationship that involves emotional or physical closeness between people and may include sexual intimacy and feelings of romance or love.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Intimate relationships are interdependent, and the members of the relationship mutually influence each other.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The quality and nature of the relationship depends on the interactions between individuals, and is derived from the unique context and history that builds between people over time.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Romantic relationships have been defined in countless ways, by writers, philosophers, religions, scientists, and in the modern day, relationship counselors.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Theories of love include Sternberg's triangular theory of love and biology of romantic love.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Sternberg defines love in terms of intimacy, passion, and commitment, which he claims exist in varying levels in different romantic relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Romantic relationships can have great social and cultural variability, and may for example exist without any sexual intimacy, between people of any gender, or among a group of people, as in polyamory or open relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] While many individuals recognize the single defining quality of a romantic relationship as the presence of love, it is impossible for romantic relationships to survive without the component of interpersonal communication.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Within romantic relationships, love is therefore equally difficult to define.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Hazan and Shaver define love, using Ainsworth's attachment theory, as comprising proximity, emotional support, self-exploration, and separation distress when parted from the loved one.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Other components commonly associated with love are physical attraction, similarity, reciprocity, and self-disclosure.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Early adolescent relationships are characterized by companionship, reciprocity, and sexual experiences.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] As emerging adults mature, they begin to develop attachment and caring qualities in their relationships, including love, bonding, security, and support for partners.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Earlier relationships also tend to be shorter and exhibit greater involvement with social networks.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Later relationships are often marked by shrinking social networks, as the couple dedicates more time to each other than to associates.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Later relationships also tend to exhibit higher levels of commitment.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Most psychologists and relationship counselors predict a decline of intimacy and passion over time, replaced by a greater emphasis on companionate love (differing from adolescent companionate love in the caring, committed, and partner-focused qualities).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] However, couple studies have found no decline in intimacy nor in the importance of sex, intimacy, and passionate love to those in longer or later-life relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Older people tend to be more satisfied in their relationships, but face greater barriers to entering new relationships than do younger or middle-aged people.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Older women in particular face social, demographic, and personal barriers; men aged 65 and older are nearly twice as likely as women to be married, and widowers are nearly three times as likely to be dating 18 months following their partner's loss compared to widows.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The term *significant other* gained popularity during the 1990s, reflecting the growing acceptance of 'non-heteronormative' relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] It can be used to avoid making an assumption about the gender or relational status (e.g. married, cohabitating, civil union) of a person's intimate partner.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Cohabiting relationships continue to rise, with many partners considering cohabitation to be nearly as serious as, or a substitute for, marriage.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In particular, LGBTQ+ people often face unique challenges in establishing and maintaining intimate relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] LGBTQ+ youth also lack the social support and peer connections enjoyed by hetero-normative young people.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Nonetheless, comparative studies of homosexual and heterosexual couples have found few differences in relationship intensity, quality, satisfaction, or commitment.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Although nontraditional relationships continue to rise, marriage still makes up the majority of relationships except among emerging adults.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] It is also still considered by many to occupy a place of greater importance among family and social structures.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In ancient times, parent–child relationships were often marked by fear, either of rebellion or abandonment, resulting in the strict filial roles in, for example, ancient Rome and China.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Freud conceived of the Oedipal complex, the supposed obsession that young boys have towards their mothers and the accompanying fear and rivalry with their fathers, and the Electra complex, in which the young girl feels that her mother has castrated her and therefore becomes obsessed with her father.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Freud's ideas influenced thought on parent–child relationships for decades.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Another early conception of parent–child relationships was that love only existed as a biological drive for survival and comfort on the child's part.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In 1958, however, Harry Harlow's study "The Hot Wire Mother'' comparing rhesus' reactions to wire surrogate "mothers" and cloth "mothers" demonstrated that affection was wanted by any caregiver and not only the surrogate mothers.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The study laid the groundwork for Mary Ainsworth's attachment theory, showing how the infants used their cloth "mothers" as a secure base from which to explore.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In a series of studies using the *strange situation*, a scenario in which an infant is separated from then reunited with the parent, Ainsworth defined three styles of parent-child relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Secure attachments are linked to better social and academic outcomes and greater moral internalization as research proposes the idea that parent-child relationships play a key role in the developing morality of young children.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Secure attachments are also linked to less delinquency for children, and have been found to predict later relationship success.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For most of the late nineteenth through the twentieth century, the perception of adolescent-parent relationships was that of a time of upheaval.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Stanley Hall popularized the "Sturm und drang", or storm and stress, model of adolescence.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Psychological research has painted a much tamer picture.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Although adolescents are more risk-seeking and emerging adults have higher suicide rates, they are largely less volatile and have much better relationships with their parents than the storm and stress model would suggest.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Early adolescence often marks a decline in parent-child relationship quality, which then re-stabilizes through adolescence, and relationships are sometimes better in late adolescence than prior to its onset.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] With the increasing average age at marriage and more youths attending college and living with parents past their teens, the concept of a new period called emerging adulthood gained popularity.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This is considered a period of uncertainty and experimentation between adolescence and adulthood.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] During this stage, interpersonal relationships are considered to be more self-focused, and relationships with parents may still be influential.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Sibling relationships have a profound effect on social, psychological, emotional, and academic outcomes.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Although proximity and contact usually decreases over time, sibling bonds continue to have effect throughout their lives.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Sibling bonds are one of few enduring relationships humans may experience.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Sibling relationships are affected by parent-child relationships, such that sibling relationships in childhood often reflect the positive or negative aspects of children's relationships with their parents.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Business is generally held to be distinct from personal relations, a contrasting mode which other than excursions from the norm is based on non-personal interest and rational rather than emotional concerns.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Interpersonal relationships are dynamic systems that change continuously during their existence, and have a beginning, a lifespan, and an end.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] They tend to grow and improve gradually, as people become acquainted and become closer emotionally, or they gradually deteriorate as people drift apart, move on with their lives and form new relationships with others.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] One of the most influential models of relationship development was proposed by psychologist George Levinger.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This model was formulated to describe heterosexual, adult romantic relationships, but it has been applied to other kinds of interpersonal relations as well.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] *Buildup* – During this stage, people begin to trust and care about each other.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The need for intimacy, compatibility and such filtering agents as common background and goals will influence whether or not interaction continues.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] *Continuation* – This stage follows a mutual commitment to quite a strong and close long-term friendship, romantic relationship, or even marriage.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] It is generally a long, relatively stable period.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Nevertheless, continued growth and development will occur during this time.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Mutual trust is important for sustaining the relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] *Deterioration* – Not all relationships deteriorate, but those that do tend to show signs of trouble.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Boredom, resentment, and dissatisfaction may occur, and individuals may communicate less and avoid self-disclosure.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Loss of trust and betrayals may take place as the downward spiral continues, eventually ending the relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] *Ending* – The final stage marks the end of the relationship, either by breakups, death or by spatial separation for quite some time and severing all existing ties of either friendship or romantic love.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] According to the latest *Systematic Review of the Economic Literature on the Factors associated with Life Satisfaction* (dating from 2007), stable and secure relationships are beneficial, and correspondingly, relationship dissolution is harmful.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The American Psychological Association has summarized the evidence on breakups.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Breaking up can actually be a positive experience when the relationship did not expand the self and when the breakup leads to personal growth.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Less time between a breakup and a subsequent relationship predicts higher self-esteem, attachment security, emotional stability, respect for your new partner, and greater well-being.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Furthermore, rebound relationships do not last any shorter than regular relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] 60% of people are friends with one or more ex.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] 60% of people have had an off-and-on relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] 37% of cohabiting couples, and 23% of the married, have broken up and gotten back together with their existing partner.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Terminating a marital relationship implies divorce or annulment.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] One reason cited for divorce is infidelity.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The determinants of unfaithfulness are debated by dating service providers, feminists, academics, and science communicators.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] According to Psychology Today, women's, rather than men's, level of commitment more strongly determines if a relationship will continue.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Abusive relationships involve either maltreatment or violence such as physical abuse, physical neglect, sexual abuse, and emotional maltreatment.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Abusive relationships within the family are very prevalent in the United States and usually involve women or children as victims.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Common individual factors for abusers include low self-esteem, poor impulse control, external locus of control, drug use, alcohol abuse, and negative affectivity.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] There are also external factors such as stress, poverty, and loss which contribute to likelihood of abuse.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Codependency initially focused on a codependent partner enabling substance abuse, but it has become more broadly defined to describe a dysfunctional relationship with one or both partners having extreme dependence on or preoccupation with the relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, a narcissist and a sycophant with abandonment issues may create codependency as the narcissist values the flattery from the sycophant and the sycophant values the narcissist's approval.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] There are some who even refer to codependency as an addiction to the relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The focus of codependents tends to be on the emotional state, behavioral choices, thoughts, and beliefs of another person.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Often those who are codependent neglect themselves in favor of taking care of others and have difficulty fully developing an identity of their own.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Narcissists focus on themselves and often distance themselves from intimate relationships; the focus of narcissistic interpersonal relationships is to promote one's self-concept.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Generally, narcissists show less empathy in relationships and view love pragmatically or as a game involving others' emotions.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Narcissists are usually part of the personality disorder, narcissistic personality disorder (NPD).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In relationships, they tend to affect the other person as they attempt to use them to enhance their self-esteem.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Specific types of NPD make a person incapable of having an interpersonal relationship due to their being cunning, envious, and contemptuous.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Human beings are innately social and are shaped by their experiences with others.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] There are multiple perspectives to understand this inherent motivation to interact with others.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] According to Maslow's hierarchy of needs, humans need to feel love (sexual/nonsexual) and acceptance from social groups (family, peer groups).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In fact, the need to belong is so innately ingrained that it may be strong enough to overcome physiological and safety needs, such as children's attachment to abusive parents or staying in abusive romantic relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Such examples illustrate the extent to which the psychobiological drive to belong is entrenched.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Another way to appreciate the importance of relationships is in terms of a reward framework.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This perspective suggests that individuals engage in relations that are rewarding in both tangible and intangible ways.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The concept fits into a larger theory of social exchange.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This theory is based on the idea that relationships develop as a result of cost–benefit analysis.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Individuals seek out rewards in interactions with others and are willing to pay a cost for said rewards.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In the best-case scenario, rewards will exceed costs, producing a net gain.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This can lead to "shopping around" or constantly comparing alternatives to maximize the benefits or rewards while minimizing costs.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Relationships are also important for their ability to help individuals develop a sense of self.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The relational self is the part of an individual's self-concept that consists of the feelings and beliefs that one has regarding oneself that develops based on interactions with others.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In other words, one's emotions and behaviors are shaped by prior relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Relational self theory posits that prior and existing relationships influence one's emotions and behaviors in interactions with new individuals, particularly those individuals that remind them of others in their life.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Studies have shown that exposure to someone who resembles a significant other activates specific self-beliefs, changing how one thinks about oneself in the moment more so than exposure to someone who does not resemble one's significant other.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Power is the ability to influence the behavior of other people.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] When two parties have or assert unequal levels of power, one is termed "dominant" and the other "submissive".
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Expressions of dominance can communicate an intention to assert or maintain dominance in a relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Being submissive can be beneficial because it saves time, limits emotional stress, and may avoid hostile actions such as withholding of resources, cessation of cooperation, termination of the relationship, maintaining a grudge, or even physical violence.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Submission occurs in different degrees; for example, some employees may follow orders without question, whereas others might express disagreement but concede when pressed.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Groups of people can form a dominance hierarchy.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, a hierarchical organization uses a command hierarchy for top-down management.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This contrasts with group decision-making and systems which encourage decision-making and self-organization by front-line employees, who in some cases may have better information about customer needs or how to work efficiently.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Dominance is only one aspect of organizational structure.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] A power structure describes power and dominance relationships in a larger society.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, a feudal society under a monarchy exhibits a strong dominance hierarchy in both economics and physical power, whereas dominance relationships in a society with democracy and capitalism are more complicated.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In business relationships, dominance is often associated with economic power.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, a business may adopt a submissive attitude to customer preferences (stocking what customers want to buy) and complaints ("the customer is always right") in order to earn more money.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] A firm with monopoly power may be less responsive to customer complaints because it can afford to adopt a dominant position.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] In a business partnership a "silent partner" is one who adopts a submissive position in all aspects, but retains financial ownership and a share of the profits.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Two parties can be dominant in different areas.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, in a friendship or romantic relationship, one person may have strong opinions about where to eat dinner, whereas the other has strong opinions about how to decorate a shared space.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] It could be beneficial for the party with weak preferences to be submissive in that area because it will not make them unhappy and avoids conflict with the party that would be unhappy.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The breadwinner model is associated with gender role assignments where the male in a heterosexual marriage would be dominant as they are responsible for economic provision.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Relationship quality refers to the perceived quality of a close relationship (i.e., romantic relationship, friendship, or family).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Relationship quality (sometimes used interchangeably with relationship satisfaction, relationship flourishing, or relationship happiness), in the context of close interpersonal relationships is generally defined as a reflection of a couple's overall feelings towards their relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] More simply, it is the extent to which members in a relationship (romantic or otherwise) view their relationship as positive or negative.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The determinant of relationship quality is often a variety of self-reported evaluations of traits that make up relationship quality.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For instance, feelings of closeness may be measured via questions that ask an individual to rate the extent to which they identify with statements.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] I.e., "I feel close to my partner", "I am comfortable sharing personal thoughts and feelings with my partner", etc.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] These questions are typically asked on a Likert scale and the average of those scores represents an individual's feelings of closeness toward their partner.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Some scales are considered unidimensional and attempt to directly measure the construct of relationship quality.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Other scales, considered multidimensional, repeat this process for other hypothesized components (e.g., closeness and satisfaction) before aggregating dimensions into a representative "relationship quality" score.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Historically, relationship quality has been the most commonly studied in the context of intimate romantic relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] More recently, the study of relationship quality has extended to include other types of close relationships (see: friendships, family, sibling, parent).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] There is not always agreement among scholars about what domains should be included in the measurement of relationship quality, even within the different types of close relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Despite this, relationship quality and its predictors have been of popular interest to relationship scholars due to the range of psychological and relational outcomes that high quality relationships have been positively linked and associated with.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Social exchange theory and Rusbult's investment model show that relationship satisfaction is based on three factors: rewards, costs, and comparison levels (Miller, 2012).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Rewards refer to any aspects of the partner or relationship that are positive.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Conversely, costs are the negative or unpleasant aspects of the partner or their relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The comparison level includes what each partner expects of the relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The comparison level is influenced by past relationships, and general relationship expectations they are taught by family and friends.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Individuals in long-distance relationships, LDRs, rated their relationships as more satisfying than individuals in proximal relationship, PRs.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Alternatively, Holt and Stone (1988) found that long-distance couples who were able to meet with their partner at least once a month had similar satisfaction levels to unmarried couples who cohabitated.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Also, the relationship satisfaction was lower for members of LDRs who saw their partner less frequently than once a month.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] LDR couples reported the same level of relationship satisfaction as couples in PRs, despite only seeing each other on average once every 23 days.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Social exchange theory and the am investment model both theorize that relationships that are high in cost would be less satisfying than relationships that are low in cost.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] LDRs have a higher level of costs than PRs, therefore, one would assume that LDRs are less satisfying than PRs.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Individuals in LDRs are more satisfied with their relationships compared to individuals in PRs.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This can be explained by unique aspects of the LDRs, how the individuals use relationship maintenance behaviors, and the attachment styles of the individuals in the relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Therefore, the costs and benefits of the relationship are subjective to the individual, and people in LDRs tend to report lower costs and higher rewards in their relationship compared to PRs.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Confucianism is a study and theory of relationships, especially within hierarchies.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Social harmony—the central goal of Confucianism—results in part from every individual knowing their place in the social order and playing their part well.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Particular duties arise from each person's particular situation in relation to others.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The individual stands simultaneously in several different relationships with different people: as a junior in relation to parents and elders; and as a senior in relation to younger siblings, students, and others.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Juniors are considered in Confucianism to owe their seniors reverence and seniors have duties of benevolence and concern toward juniors.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] A focus on mutuality is prevalent in East Asian cultures to this day.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] The mindfulness theory of relationships shows how closeness in relationships may be enhanced.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Popular perceptions of intimate relationships are strongly influenced by movies and television.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Common messages are that love is predestined, love at first sight is possible, and that love with the right person always succeeds.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Those who consume the most romance-related media tend to believe in predestined romance and that those who are destined to be together implicitly understand each other.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] These beliefs, however, can lead to less communication and problem-solving as well as giving up on relationships more easily when conflict is encountered.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Social media has changed the face of interpersonal relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Romantic interpersonal relationships are no less impacted.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, in the United States, Facebook has become an integral part of the dating process for emerging adults.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Social media can have both positive and negative impacts on romantic relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, supportive social networks have been linked to more stable relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] However, social media usage can also facilitate conflict, jealousy, and passive-aggressive behaviors such as spying on a partner.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Aside from direct effects on the development, maintenance, and perception of romantic relationships, excessive social network usage is linked to jealousy and dissatisfaction in relationships.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Another common behavior in online communities, including dating, is lurking.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Lurking means watching communities without posting or replying.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Some say it means never posting, while others say even small posts count (Neelen & Fetter, 2010; Golder & Donath, 2004).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Lurking is often seen negatively, tied to "freeloading" (Preece, Nonnecke, & Andrews, 2004), but others see it as valid participation.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Lurking depends on personal goals, personality, and group dynamics.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] For example, introverts tend to lurk more, and people with higher tech confidence participate more (Ross et al., 2009; Sun, Rau, & Ma, 2014).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Studies show up to 90% of users may lurk at some point (Muller, 2012).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Lurking can help gather info or support without interacting, but it can make a community seem less active, Lurking can make online relationships feel one-sided because it reduces interaction.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] When someone just watches without joining in, it can create distance and make it harder to build trust.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] This can slow down the growth of a real connection.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Understanding lurking can help encourage more participation (Yeow, Johnson, & Faraj, 2006).
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] A growing segment of the population is engaging in purely online dating, sometimes but not always moving towards traditional face-to-face interactions.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] These online relationships differ from face-to-face relationships; for example, self-disclosure may be of primary importance in developing an online relationship.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Conflict management differs, since avoidance is easier and conflict resolution skills may not develop in the same way.
[src:william-s-condon/human-interaction] Additionally, the definition of infidelity is both broadened and narrowed, since physical infidelity becomes easier to conceal but emotional infidelity (e.g. chatting with more than one online partner) becomes a more serious offense.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Language acquisition involves structures, rules, and representation.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The capacity to successfully use language requires human beings to acquire a range of tools, including phonology, morphology, syntax, semantics, and an extensive vocabulary.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Language can be vocalized as in speech, or manual as in sign.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Human language capacity is represented in the brain.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Even though human language capacity is finite, one can say and understand an effectively infinite number of sentences, which is based on a syntactic principle called recursion.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Evidence suggests that every individual has three recursive mechanisms that allow sentences to go indeterminately.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These three mechanisms are: *relativization*, *complementation* and *coordination*.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] There are two main guiding principles in first-language acquisition: speech perception always precedes speech production, and the gradually evolving system by which a child learns a language is built up one step at a time, beginning with the distinction between individual phonemes.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] For many years, linguists interested in child language acquisition have questioned how language is acquired.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Language acquisition usually refers to **first-language acquisition**.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It studies infants' acquisition of their native language, whether that is a spoken language or a sign language, though it can also refer to **bilingual first language acquisition** (BFLA), referring to an infant's simultaneous acquisition of two native languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This is distinguished from *second-language acquisition*, which deals with the acquisition (in both children and adults) of additional languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] On top of speech, reading and writing a language with an entirely different script increases the complexities of true foreign language literacy.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Language acquisition is one of the quintessential human traits.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Some early observation-based ideas about language acquisition were proposed by Plato, who felt that word-meaning mapping in some form was innate.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Empiricists, like Thomas Hobbes and John Locke, argued that knowledge (and, for Locke, language) emerge ultimately from abstracted sense impressions.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Proponents of behaviorism argued that language may be learned through a form of operant conditioning.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Skinner's *Verbal Behavior* (1957), he suggested that the successful use of a sign, such as a word or lexical unit, given a certain stimulus, reinforces its "momentary" or contextual probability.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Since operant conditioning is contingent on reinforcement by rewards, a child would learn that a specific combination of sounds means a specific thing through repeated successful associations made between the two.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Some empiricist theories of language acquisition include the statistical learning theory.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Hockett of language acquisition, relational frame theory, functionalist linguistics, social interactionist theory, and usage-based language acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Instead, children typically follow a pattern of using an irregular form of a word correctly, making errors later on, and eventually returning to the proper use of the word.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] For example, a child may correctly learn the word "gave" (past tense of "give"), and later on use the word "gived".
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Eventually, the child will typically go back to using the correct word, "gave".
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Chomsky claimed the pattern is difficult to attribute to Skinner's idea of operant conditioning as the primary way that children acquire language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Chomsky argued that if language were solely acquired through behavioral conditioning, children would not likely learn the proper use of a word and suddenly use the word incorrectly.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Chomsky believed that Skinner failed to account for the central role of syntactic knowledge in language competence.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Chomsky also rejected the term "learning", which Skinner used to claim that children "learn" language through operant conditioning.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Instead, Chomsky argued for a mathematical approach to language acquisition, based on a study of syntax.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The capacity to acquire and use language is a key aspect that distinguishes humans from other beings.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Although it is difficult to pin down what aspects of language are uniquely human, there are a few design features that can be found in all known forms of human language, but that are missing from forms of animal communication.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] For example, many animals are able to communicate with each other by signaling to the things around them, but this kind of communication lacks the arbitrariness of human vernaculars (in that there is nothing about the sound of the word "dog" that would hint at its meaning).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Other forms of animal communication may utilize arbitrary sounds, but are unable to combine those sounds in different ways to create completely novel messages that can then be automatically understood by another.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Hockett called this design feature of human language "productivity".
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It is crucial to the understanding of human language acquisition that humans are not limited to a finite set of words, but, rather, must be able to understand and utilize a complex system that allows for an infinite number of possible messages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] So, while many forms of animal communication exist, they differ from human language in that they have a limited range of vocabulary tokens, and the vocabulary items are not combined syntactically to create phrases.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Terrace conducted a study on a chimpanzee known as Nim Chimpsky in an attempt to teach him American Sign Language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This study was an attempt to further research done with a chimpanzee named Washoe, who was reportedly able to acquire American Sign Language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] However, upon further inspection, Terrace concluded that both experiments were failures.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] While Nim was able to acquire signs, he never acquired a knowledge of grammar, and was unable to combine signs in a meaningful way.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Researchers noticed that "signs that seemed spontaneous were, in fact, cued by teachers", and not actually productive.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] When Terrace reviewed Project Washoe, he found similar results.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] He postulated that there is a fundamental difference between animals and humans in their motivation to learn language; animals, such as in Nim's case, are motivated only by physical reward, while humans learn language in order to "create a new type of communication".
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In another language acquisition study, Jean-Marc-Gaspard Itard attempted to teach Victor of Aveyron, a feral child, how to speak.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Victor was able to learn a few words, but ultimately never fully acquired language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Slightly more successful was a study done on Genie, another child never introduced to society.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] She had been entirely isolated for the first thirteen years of her life by her father.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Caretakers and researchers attempted to measure her ability to learn a language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] She was able to acquire a large vocabulary, but never acquired grammatical knowledge.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Researchers concluded that the theory of a critical period was true — Genie was too old to learn how to speak productively, although she was still able to comprehend language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] A major debate in understanding language acquisition is how these capacities are picked up by infants from the linguistic input.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Input in the linguistic context is defined as "All words, contexts, and other forms of language to which a learner is exposed, relative to acquired proficiency in first or second languages".
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Nativists such as Chomsky have focused on the hugely complex nature of human grammars, the finiteness and ambiguity of the input that children receive, and the relatively limited cognitive abilities of an infant.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] From these characteristics, they conclude that the process of language acquisition in infants must be tightly constrained and guided by the biologically given characteristics of the human brain.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Otherwise, they argue, it is extremely difficult to explain how children, within the first five years of life, routinely master the complex, largely tacit grammatical rules of their native language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Additionally, the evidence of such rules in their native language is all indirect—adult speech to children cannot encompass all of what children know by the time they have acquired their native language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Other scholars, however, have resisted the possibility that infants' routine success at acquiring the grammar of their native language requires anything more than the forms of learning seen with other cognitive skills, including such mundane motor skills as learning to ride a bike.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In particular, there has been resistance to the possibility that human biology includes any form of specialization for language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This conflict is often referred to as the "nature and nurture" debate.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The as-yet unresolved question is the extent to which the specific cognitive capacities in the "nature" component are also used outside of language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Emergentist theories, such as Brian MacWhinney's competition model, posit that language acquisition is a cognitive process that emerges from the interaction of biological pressures and the environment.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] According to these theories, neither nature nor nurture alone is sufficient to trigger language learning; both of these influences must work together in order to allow children to acquire a language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The proponents of these theories argue that general cognitive processes subserve language acquisition and that the result of these processes is language-specific phenomena, such as word learning and grammar acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The findings of many empirical studies support the predictions of these theories, suggesting that language acquisition is a more complex process than many have proposed.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] On the other hand, cognitive-functional theorists use this anthropological data to show how human beings have evolved the capacity for grammar and syntax to meet our demand for linguistic symbols.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Further, the generative theory has several constructs (such as movement, empty categories, complex underlying structures, and strict binary branching) that cannot possibly be acquired from any amount of linguistic input.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It is unclear that human language is actually *anything like* the generative conception of it.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Since language, as imagined by nativists, is unlearnably complex, subscribers to this theory argue that it must, therefore, be innate.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Nativists hypothesize that some features of syntactic categories exist even before a child is exposed to any experience—categories on which children map words of their language as they learn their native language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] A different theory of language, however, may yield different conclusions.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] While all theories of language acquisition posit some degree of innateness, they vary in how much value they place on this innate capacity to acquire language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Empiricism places less value on the innate knowledge, arguing instead that the input, combined with both general and language-specific learning capacities, is sufficient for acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] During the 1990s and 2000s, the debate surrounding the nativist position has centered on whether the inborn capabilities are language-specific or domain-general, such as those that enable the infant to visually make sense of the world in terms of objects and actions.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The anti-nativist view has many strands, but a frequent theme is that language emerges from usage in social contexts, using learning mechanisms that are a part of an innate general cognitive learning apparatus.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This position has been championed by David M.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Powers, Elizabeth Bates, Catherine Snow, Anat Ninio, Brian MacWhinney, Michael Tomasello, Michael Ramscar, William O'Grady, and others.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Philosophers, such as Fiona Cowie and Barbara Scholz with Geoffrey Pullum have also argued against certain nativist claims in support of empiricism.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The new field of cognitive linguistics has emerged as a specific counter to Chomsky's Generative Grammar and to Nativism.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Some language acquisition researchers, such as Elissa Newport, Richard Aslin, and Jenny Saffran, emphasize the possible roles of general learning mechanisms, especially statistical learning, in language acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The development of connectionist models that when implemented are able to successfully learn words and syntactical conventions supports the predictions of statistical learning theories of language acquisition, as do empirical studies of children's detection of word boundaries.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In a series of connectionist model simulations, Franklin Chang has demonstrated that such a domain general statistical learning mechanism could explain a wide range of language structure acquisition phenomena.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Statistical learning theory suggests that, when learning language, a learner would use the natural statistical properties of language to deduce its structure, including sound patterns, words, and the beginnings of grammar.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] That is, language learners are sensitive to how often syllable combinations or words occur in relation to other syllables.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Infants between 21 and 23 months old are also able to use statistical learning to develop "lexical categories", such as an animal category, which infants might later map to newly learned words in the same category.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These findings suggest that early experience listening to language is critical to vocabulary acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The statistical abilities are effective, but also limited by what qualifies as input, what is done with that input, and by the structure of the resulting output.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Statistical learning (and more broadly, distributional learning) can be accepted as a component of language acquisition by researchers on either side of the "nature and nurture" debate.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] From the perspective of that debate, an important question is whether statistical learning can, by itself, serve as an alternative to nativist explanations for the grammatical constraints of human language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The central idea of these theories is that language development occurs through the incremental acquisition of meaningful chunks of elementary constituents, which can be words, phonemes, or syllables.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Several studies conducted in 2005–2007 demonstrated the efficacy of this approach in simulating several phenomena in the acquisition of syntactic categories and the acquisition of phonological knowledge.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Research has demonstrated that infants as young as 3–5 months can abstract phonological features amodally, i.e., recognising place of articulation across multiple consonants regardless of whether speech is heard or seen.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These early abstraction abilities have been shown to change developmentally across the first year and predict later vocabulary size.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Chunking theories of language acquisition constitute a group of theories related to statistical learning theories, in that they assume that the input from the environment plays an essential role; however, they postulate different learning mechanisms.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Researchers at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology have developed a computer model analyzing early toddler conversations to predict the structure of later conversations.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] They showed that toddlers develop their own individual rules for speaking, with 'slots' into which they put certain kinds of words.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] A significant outcome of this research is that rules inferred from toddler speech were better predictors of subsequent speech than traditional grammars.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Chunking for this model was shown to be most effective in learning a first language but was able to create utterances learning a second language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The relational frame theory (RFT) (Hayes, Barnes-Holmes, Roche, 2001), provides a wholly selectionist/learning account of the origin and development of language competence and complexity.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Based upon the principles of Skinnerian behaviorism, RFT posits that children acquire language purely through interacting with the environment.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] RFT theorists introduced the concept of functional contextualism in language learning, which emphasizes the importance of predicting and influencing psychological events, such as thoughts, feelings, and behaviors, by focusing on manipulable variables in their own context.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] RFT distinguishes itself from Skinner's work by identifying and defining a particular type of operant conditioning known as derived relational responding, a learning process that, to date, appears to occur only in humans possessing a capacity for language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Empirical studies supporting the predictions of RFT suggest that children learn language through a system of inherent reinforcements, challenging the view that language acquisition is based upon innate, language-specific cognitive capacities.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Social interactionist theory is an explanation of language development emphasizing the role of social interaction between the developing child and linguistically knowledgeable adults.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It is based largely on the socio-cultural theories of Soviet psychologist Lev Vygotsky, and was made prominent in the Western world by Jerome Bruner.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Unlike other approaches, it emphasizes the role of feedback and reinforcement in language acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Specifically, it asserts that much of a child's linguistic growth stems from modeling of and interaction with parents and other adults, who very frequently provide instructive correction.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It is thus somewhat similar to behaviorist accounts of language learning.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It differs substantially, though, in that it posits the existence of a social-cognitive model and other mental structures within children (a sharp contrast to the "black box" approach of classical behaviorism).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Another key idea within the theory of social interactionism is that of the zone of proximal development.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This is a theoretical construct denoting the set of tasks a child is capable of performing with guidance but not alone.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] As applied to language, it describes the set of linguistic tasks (for example, proper syntax, suitable vocabulary usage) that a child cannot carry out on its own at a given time, but can learn to carry out if assisted by an able adult.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] A child will use short expressions such as *Bye-bye Mummy* or *All-gone milk*, which actually are combinations of individual nouns and an operator, before they begin to produce gradually more complex sentences.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In the 1990s, within the principles and parameters framework, this hypothesis was extended into a maturation-based structure building model of child language regarding the acquisition of functional categories.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In this model, children are seen as gradually building up more and more complex structures, with lexical categories (like noun and verb) being acquired before functional-syntactic categories (like determiner and complementizer).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It is also often found that in acquiring a language, the most frequently used verbs are irregular verbs.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In learning English, for example, young children first begin to learn the past tense of verbs individually.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] However, when they acquire a "rule", such as adding *-ed* to form the past tense, they begin to exhibit occasional overgeneralization errors (e.g.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] "runned", "hitted") alongside correct past tense forms.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] One influential proposal regarding the origin of this type of error suggests that the adult state of grammar stores each irregular verb form in memory and also includes a "block" on the use of the regular rule for forming that type of verb.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In the developing child's mind, retrieval of that "block" may fail, causing the child to erroneously apply the regular rule instead of retrieving the irregular.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] A-movement such as passives (["The apple was eaten by [John (ate the apple)"]]), or raising ["Some work does seem to remain [(There) does seem to remain (some work)"]]).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In terms of a merge-based theory of language acquisition, complements and specifiers are simply notations for first-merge (= "complement-of" [head-complement]), and later second-merge (= "specifier-of" [specifier-head], with merge always forming to a head.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] First-merge establishes only a set {a, b} and is not an ordered pair—e.g., an {N, N}-compound of 'boat-house' would allow the ambiguous readings of either 'a kind of house' and/or 'a kind of boat'.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It is only with second-merge that order is derived out of a set {a {a, b}} which yields the recursive properties of syntax—e.g., a 'house-boat' {house {house, boat}} now reads unambiguously only as a 'kind of boat'.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It is this property of recursion that allows for projection and labeling of a phrase to take place; in this case, that the Noun 'boat' is the Head of the compound, and 'house' acting as a kind of specifier/modifier.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] External-merge (first-merge) establishes substantive 'base structure' inherent to the VP, yielding theta/argument structure, and may go beyond the lexical-category VP to involve the functional-category light verb vP.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Internal-merge (second-merge) establishes more formal aspects related to edge-properties of scope and discourse-related material pegged to CP.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In a Phase-based theory, this twin vP/CP distinction follows the "duality of semantics" discussed within the Minimalist Program, and is further developed into a dual distinction regarding a probe-goal relation.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] As a consequence, at the "external/first-merge-only" stage, young children would show an inability to interpret readings from a given ordered pair, since they would only have access to the mental parsing of a non-recursive set.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] (See Roeper for a full discussion of recursion in child language acquisition).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Generative grammar, associated especially with the work of Noam Chomsky, is currently one of the approaches to explaining children's acquisition of syntax.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Its leading idea is that human biology imposes narrow constraints on the child's "hypothesis space" during language acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] An important argument which favors the generative approach, is the poverty of the stimulus argument.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The child's input (a finite number of sentences encountered by the child, together with information about the context in which they were uttered) is, in principle, compatible with an infinite number of conceivable grammars.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Additionally, when children do understand that they are being corrected, they don't always reproduce accurate restatements.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Yet, barring situations of medical abnormality or extreme privation, all children in a given speech-community converge on very much the same grammar by the age of about five years.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Considerations such as those have led Chomsky, Jerry Fodor, Eric Lenneberg and others to argue that the types of grammar the child needs to consider must be narrowly constrained by human biology (the nativist position).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These innate constraints are sometimes referred to as universal grammar, the human "language faculty", or the "language instinct".
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The comparative method of crosslinguistic research applies the comparative method used in historical linguistics to psycholinguistic research.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In historical linguistics the comparative method uses comparisons between historically related languages to reconstruct a proto-language and trace the history of each daughter language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The comparative method can be repurposed for research on language acquisition by comparing historically related child languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The historical ties within each language family provide a roadmap for research.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] For Indo-European languages, the comparative method would first compare language acquisition within the Slavic, Celtic, Germanic, Romance and Indo-Iranian branches of the family before attempting broader comparisons between the branches.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] For Otomanguean languages, the comparative method would first compare language acquisition within the Oto-pamean, Chinantecan, Tlapanecan, Popolocan, Zapotecan, Amuzgan and Mixtecan branches before attempting broader comparisons between the branches.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The comparative method imposes an evaluation standard for assessing the languages used in language acquisition research.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The comparative method derives its power by assembling comprehensive datasets for each language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Descriptions of the prosody and phonology for each language inform analyses of morphology and the lexicon, which in turn inform analyses of syntax and conversational styles.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Information on prosodic structure in one language informs research on the prosody of the related languages and vice versa.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The comparative method produces a cumulative research program in which each description contributes to a comprehensive description of language acquisition for each language within a family as well as across the languages within each branch of the language family.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Comparative studies of language acquisition control the number of extraneous factors that impact language development.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Speakers of historically related languages typically share a common culture that may include similar lifestyles and child-rearing practices.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Historically related languages have similar phonologies and morphologies that impact early lexical and syntactic development in similar ways.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The comparative method predicts that children acquiring historically related languages will exhibit similar patterns of language development, and that these common patterns may not hold in historically unrelated languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The acquisition of Dutch will resemble the acquisition of German, but not the acquisition of Totonac or Mixtec.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] A claim about any universal of language acquisition must control for the shared grammatical structures that languages inherit from a common ancestor.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Several language acquisition studies have accidentally employed features of the comparative method due to the availability of datasets from historically related languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Research on the acquisition of the Romance and Scandinavian languages used aspects of the comparative method, but did not produce detailed comparisons across different levels of grammar.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The most advanced use of the comparative method to date appears in research on the acquisition of the Mayan languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This research has yielded detailed comparative studies on the acquisition of phonological, lexical, morphological and syntactic features in eight Mayan languages as well as comparisons of language input and language socialization.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Several regions of the human brain participate in the reception, comprehension and production of language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These include the classical 'primary' language centers - Wernicke's area and Broca's area - along with several other brain structures.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Recent advances in functional neuroimaging technology have allowed for a better understanding of how language acquisition is manifested physically in the brain.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Language acquisition almost always occurs in children during a period of rapid increase in brain volume.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] At this point in development, a child has many more neural connections than he or she will have as an adult, allowing for the child to be more able to learn new things than he or she would be as an adult.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Language acquisition has been studied from the perspective of developmental psychology and neuroscience, which looks at learning to use and understand language parallel to a child's brain development.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It has been determined, through empirical research on developmentally normal children, as well as through some extreme cases of language deprivation, that there is a "sensitive period" of language acquisition in which human infants have the ability to learn any language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Several researchers have found that from birth until the age of six months, infants can discriminate the phonetic contrasts of all languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Researchers believe that this gives infants the ability to acquire the language spoken around them.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] After this age, the child is able to perceive only the phonemes specific to the language being learned.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The reduced phonemic sensitivity enables children to build phonemic categories and recognize stress patterns and sound combinations specific to the language they are acquiring.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] As Wilder Penfield noted, "Before the child begins to speak and to perceive, the uncommitted cortex is a blank slate on which nothing has been written.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In the ensuing years much is written, and the writing is normally never erased.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] However, there may be an age at which becoming a fluent and natural user of a language is no longer possible; Penfield and Roberts (1959) cap their sensitive period at nine years old.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The human brain *may* very well be automatically wired to learn languages, but this ability does not last into adulthood in the same way that it exists during childhood.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] By around age 12, language acquisition has typically been solidified, and it becomes more difficult to learn a language in the same way a native speaker would.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Just like children who speak, deaf children go through a critical period for learning language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Deaf children who acquire their first language later in life show lower performance in complex aspects of grammar.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] At that point, it is usually a second language that a person is trying to acquire and not a first.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Assuming that children are exposed to language during the critical period, acquiring language is almost never missed by cognitively normal children.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Humans are so well-prepared to learn language that it becomes almost impossible not to.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Researchers are unable to experimentally test the effects of the sensitive period of development on language acquisition, because it would be unethical to deprive children of language until this period is over.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] However, case studies on abused, language-deprived children show that they exhibit extreme limitations in language skills, even after instruction.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] At a very young age, children can distinguish different sounds but cannot yet produce them.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] During infancy, children begin to babble.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Deaf babies babble in the same patterns as hearing babies do, showing that babbling is not a result of babies simply imitating certain sounds, but is actually a natural part of the process of language development.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Deaf babies do, however, often babble less than hearing babies, and they begin to babble later on in infancy—at approximately 11 months as compared to approximately 6 months for hearing babies.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Prelinguistic language abilities that are crucial for language acquisition have been seen even earlier than infancy.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] There have been many different studies examining different modes of language acquisition prior to birth.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The study of language acquisition in fetuses began in the late 1980s when several researchers independently discovered that very young infants could discriminate their native language from other languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] (1988)*, infants underwent discrimination tests, and it was shown that infants as young as 4 days old could discriminate utterances in their native language from those in an unfamiliar language, but could not discriminate between two languages when neither was native to them.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These results suggest that there are mechanisms for fetal auditory learning, and other researchers have found further behavioral evidence to support this notion.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Prosody is the property of speech that conveys an emotional state of the utterance, as well as the intended form of speech, for example, question, statement or command.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Some researchers in the field of developmental neuroscience argue that fetal auditory learning mechanisms result solely from discrimination of prosodic elements.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Although this would hold merit in an evolutionary psychology perspective (i.e. recognition of mother's voice/familiar group language from emotionally valent stimuli), some theorists argue that there is more than prosodic recognition in elements of fetal learning.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Newer evidence shows that fetuses not only react to the native language differently from non-native languages, but that fetuses react differently and can accurately discriminate between native and non-native vowel sounds (Moon, Lagercrantz, & Kuhl, 2013).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Furthermore, a 2016 study showed that newborn infants encode the edges of multisyllabic sequences better than the internal components of the sequence (Ferry et al., 2016).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Together, these results suggest that newborn infants have learned important properties of syntactic processing in utero, as demonstrated by infant knowledge of native language vowels and the sequencing of heard multisyllabic phrases.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This ability to sequence specific vowels gives newborn infants some of the fundamental mechanisms needed in order to learn the complex organization of a language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] From a neuroscientific perspective, neural correlates have been found that demonstrate human fetal learning of speech-like auditory stimuli that most other studies have been analyzing (Partanen et al., 2013).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] (2013), researchers presented fetuses with certain word variants and observed that these fetuses exhibited higher brain activity in response to certain word variants as compared to controls.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Learning a new word, that is, learning to speak this word and speak it on the appropriate occasions, depends upon many factors.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] First, the learner needs to be able to hear what they are attempting to pronounce.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Also required is the capacity to engage in speech repetition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Children with reduced ability to repeat non-words (a marker of speech repetition abilities) show a slower rate of vocabulary expansion than children with normal ability.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Several computational models of vocabulary acquisition have been proposed.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Various studies have shown that the size of a child's vocabulary by the age of 24 months correlates with the child's future development and language skills.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] If a child knows fifty or fewer words by the age of 24 months, he or she is classified as a late-talker, and future language development, like vocabulary expansion and the organization of grammar, is likely to be slower and stunted.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Two more crucial elements of vocabulary acquisition are word segmentation and statistical learning (described above).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Word segmentation, or the ability to break down words into syllables from fluent speech can be accomplished by eight-month-old infants.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] By the time infants are 17 months old, they are able to link meaning to segmented words.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Recent evidence also suggests that motor skills and experiences may influence vocabulary acquisition during infancy.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Specifically, learning to sit independently between 3 and 5 months of age has been found to predict receptive vocabulary at both 10 and 14 months of age, and independent walking skills have been found to correlate with language skills at around 10 to 14 months of age.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These findings show that language acquisition is an embodied process that is influenced by a child's overall motor abilities and development.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Studies have also shown a correlation between socioeconomic status and vocabulary acquisition.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Children learn, on average, ten to fifteen new word meanings each day, but only one of these can be accounted for by direct instruction.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The other nine to fourteen word meanings must have been acquired in some other way.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It has been proposed that children acquire these meanings through processes modeled by latent semantic analysis; that is, when they encounter an unfamiliar word, children use contextual information to guess its rough meaning correctly.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] A child may expand the meaning and use of certain words that are already part of their mental lexicon in order to denominate anything that is somehow related but for which they do not know the specific word.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] For instance, a child may broaden the use of *mummy* and *dada* in order to indicate anything that belongs to their mother or father, or perhaps every person who resembles their own parents; another example might be to say *rain* while meaning *I don't want to go out*.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] There is also reason to believe that children use various heuristics to infer the meaning of words properly.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Markman and others have proposed that children assume words to refer to objects with similar properties ("cow" and "pig" might both be "animals") rather than to objects that are thematically related ("cow" and "milk" are probably not both "animals").
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Children also seem to adhere to the "whole object assumption" and think that a novel label refers to an entire entity rather than to one of its parts.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] This assumption along with other resources, such as grammar and morphological cues or lexical constraints, may help the child in acquiring word meaning, but conclusions based on such resources may sometimes conflict.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] In terms of genetics, the gene ROBO1 has been associated with phonological buffer integrity or length.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Genetic research has found two major factors predicting successful language acquisition and maintenance.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] These include inherited intelligence, and the lack of genetic anomalies that may cause speech pathologies, such as mutations in the FOXP2 gene which cause verbal dyspraxia.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The role of inherited intelligence increases with age, accounting for 20% of IQ variation in infants, and for 60% in adults.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It affects a vast variety of language-related abilities, from spatio-motor skills to writing fluency.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] There have been debates in linguistics, philosophy, psychology, and genetics, with some scholars arguing that language is fully or mostly innate, but the research evidence points to genetic factors only working in interaction with environmental ones.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Although it is difficult to determine without invasive measures which exact parts of the brain become most active and important for language acquisition, fMRI and PET technology has allowed for some conclusions to be made about where language may be centered.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Kuniyoshi Sakai has proposed, based on several neuroimaging studies, that there may be a "grammar center" in the brain, whereby language is primarily processed in the left lateral premotor cortex (located near the pre central sulcus and the inferior frontal sulcus).
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Additionally, these studies have suggested that first language and second language acquisition may be represented differently in the cortex.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] It was concluded that the brain does in fact process languages differently, but rather than being related to proficiency levels, language processing relates more to the function of the brain itself.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] During early infancy, language processing seems to occur over many areas in the brain.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] However, over time, it gradually becomes concentrated into two areas—Broca's area and Wernicke's area.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Broca's area is in the left frontal cortex and is primarily involved in the production of the patterns in vocal and sign language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] Wernicke's area is in the left temporal cortex and is primarily involved in language comprehension.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p01] The specialization of these language centers is so extensive that damage to them can result in aphasia.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] (2015: 286) comment that "There is a dawning realization that the field of child language needs data from the broadest typological array of languages and language-learning environments." This realization is part of a broader recognition in psycholinguistics for the need to document diversity.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Children's linguistic accomplishments are all the more impressive with recognition of the diversity that exists at every level of the language system.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Different levels of grammar interact in language-specific ways so that differences in morphosyntax build on differences in prosody, which in turn reflect differences in conversational style.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The diversity of adult languages results in diverse child language phenomena that challenge every acquisition theory.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] One such challenge is to explain how children acquire complex vowels in Otomanguean and other languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The complex vowels in these languages combine oral and laryngeal gestures produced with laryngeal constriction [ʔ] or laryngeal spreading [h].
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The production of the laryngealized vowels is complicated by the production of tonal contrasts, which rely upon contrasts in vocal fold vibration.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Otomanguean languages manage the conflict between tone and laryngeal gesture by timing the gesture at the start, middle or end of the vowel, e.g. ʔV, VʔV and Vʔ.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The phonetic realization of laryngealized vowels gives rise to the question of whether children acquire laryngealized vowels as single phonemes or sequences of phonemes.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The unit analysis enlarges the vowel inventory but simplifies the syllable inventory, while the sequence analysis simplifies the vowel inventory but complicates the syllable inventory.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The Otomanguean languages exhibit language-specific differences in the types and timing of the laryngeal gestures, and thus children must learn the specific laryngeal gestures that contribute to the phonological contrasts in the adult language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] An acquisition challenge in morphosyntax is to explain how children acquire ergative grammatical structures.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Ergative languages treat the subject of intransitive verbs like the object of transitive verbs at the level of morphology, syntax or both.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] At the level of morphology, ergative languages assign an ergative marker to the subject of transitive verbs.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The ergative marking may be realized by case markers on nouns or agreement markers on verbs.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] At the level of syntax, ergative languages have syntactic operations that treat the subject of transitive verbs differently from the subject of intransitive verbs.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Languages with ergative syntax like K'iche' may restrict the use of subject questions for transitive verbs but not intransitive verbs.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The acquisition challenge that ergativity creates is to explain how children acquire the language-specific manifestations of morphological and syntactic ergativity in the adult languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The Mayan language Mam has ergative agreement making on its transitive verbs but extends the ergative marking to both the subject of intransitive verbs and the object of transitive verbs yielding transitive verbs with two ergative agreement markers.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The contexts for extended ergative marking differ in type and frequency between Mayan languages, but two-year-old children produce extended ergative marking equally proficiently despite vast differences in the frequency of extended ergative marking in the adult languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Children acquire language through exposure to a diverse variety of cultural practices.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Local groups vary in size and mobility depending on their means of subsistence.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Some cultures require men to marry women who speak another language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Their children may be exposed to their mother's language for several years before moving in with their father and learning his language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Language groups have diverse beliefs about when children say their first words and what words they say.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Such beliefs shape the time when parents perceive that children understand language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] In many cultures, children hear more speech directed to others than to themselves, yet children acquire language in all cultures.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Documenting the diversity of child languages is made more urgent by the rapid loss of languages around the world.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] It may not be possible to document child language in half of the world's languages by the end of this century.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Documenting child language should be a part of every language documentation project, and has an important role to play in revitalizing local languages.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Documenting child language preserves cultural modes of language transmission and can emphasize their significance throughout the language community.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Some algorithms for language acquisition are based on statistical machine translation.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Language acquisition can be modeled as a machine learning process, which may be based on learning semantic parsers or grammar induction algorithms.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Prelingual deafness is defined as hearing loss that occurred at birth or before an individual has learned to speak.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] In the United States, 2 to 3 out of every 1000 children are born deaf or hard of hearing.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Babies who learn sign language produce signs or gestures that are more regular and more frequent than hearing babies acquiring spoken language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Just as hearing babies babble, deaf babies acquiring sign language will babble with their hands, otherwise known as manual babbling.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Therefore, as many studies have shown, language acquisition by deaf children parallels the language acquisition of a spoken language by hearing children because humans are biologically equipped for language regardless of the modality.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Deaf children's visual-manual language acquisition not only parallel spoken language acquisition but by the age of 30 months, most deaf children that were exposed to a visual language had a more advanced grasp with subject-pronoun copy rules than hearing children.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Their vocabulary bank at the ages of 12–17 months exceed that of a hearing child's, though it does even out when they reach the two-word stage.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] The use of space for absent referents and the more complex handshapes in some signs prove to be difficult for children between 5 and 9 years of age because of motor development and the complexity of remembering the spatial use.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Other options besides sign language for kids with prelingual deafness include the use of hearing aids to strengthen remaining sensory cells or cochlear implants to stimulate the hearing nerve directly.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Cochlear implants (often known simply as CIs) are hearing devices that are placed behind the ear and contain a receiver and electrodes which are placed under the skin and inside the cochlea.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Despite these developments, there is still a risk that prelingually deaf children may not develop good speech and speech reception skills.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Although cochlear implants produce sounds, they are unlike typical hearing and deaf and hard of hearing people must undergo intensive therapy in order to learn how to interpret these sounds.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] They must also learn how to speak given the range of hearing they may or may not have.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] However, deaf children of deaf parents tend to do better with language, even though they are isolated from sound and speech because their language uses a different mode of communication that is accessible to them: the visual modality of language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Although cochlear implants were initially approved for adults, now there is pressure to implant children early in order to maximize auditory skills for mainstream learning which in turn has created controversy around the topic.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Due to recent advances in technology, cochlear implants allow some deaf people to acquire some sense of hearing.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] There are interior and exposed exterior components that are surgically implanted.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Those who receive cochlear implants earlier on in life show more improvement on speech comprehension and language.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Spoken language development does vary widely for those with cochlear implants though due to a number of different factors including: age at implantation, frequency, quality and type of speech training.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Some evidence suggests that speech processing occurs at a more rapid pace in some prelingually deaf children with cochlear implants than those with traditional hearing aids.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] However, cochlear implants may not always work.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Research shows that people develop better language with a cochlear implant when they have a solid first language to rely on to understand the second language they would be learning.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] In the case of prelingually deaf children with cochlear implants, a signed language, like American Sign Language would be an accessible language for them to learn to help support the use of the cochlear implant as they learn a spoken language as their L2.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] Without a solid, accessible first language, these children run the risk of language deprivation, especially in the case that a cochlear implant fails to work.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] They would have no access to sound, meaning no access to the spoken language they are supposed to be learning.
[src:william-s-condon/language-acquisition-p02] If a signed language was not a strong language for them to use and neither was a spoken language, they now have no access to any language and run the risk of missing their critical period.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's writings often deal with the unexpected implications of research in the social sciences, such as sociology and psychology, and make frequent and extended use of academic work.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell was appointed to the Order of Canada in 2011.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell was born in Fareham, Hampshire, in England.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His mother Joyce (née Nation) Gladwell, is a Jamaican psychotherapist.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His father, Graham Gladwell, was a mathematics professor from Kent, England.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] When he was six his family moved from Southampton to the Mennonite community of Elmira, Ontario, Canada.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Throughout his childhood, Malcolm lived in rural Ontario Mennonite country, where he attended a Mennonite church.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Research done by historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. revealed that one of Gladwell's maternal ancestors was a Jamaican free woman of colour (mixed black and white) who was a slaveowner.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His great-great-great-grandmother was of Igbo ethnicity from Nigeria.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In the epilogue of his 2008 book *Outliers* he describes many lucky circumstances that came to his family over the course of several generations, contributing to his path toward success.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell has said that his mother is his role model as a writer.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's father noted that Malcolm was an unusually single-minded and ambitious boy.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] When Malcolm was 11, his father, a professor of mathematics and engineering at the University of Waterloo, allowed his son to wander around the offices at his university, which developed Malcolm's interest in reading and libraries.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In the spring of 1982, Gladwell interned with the National Journalism Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He graduated with a bachelor's degree in history from Trinity College at the University of Toronto in 1984.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell decided to pursue advertising as a career after college.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] After being rejected by every advertising agency he applied to, he accepted a journalism position at the conservative magazine *The American Spectator* and moved to Indiana.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He subsequently wrote for *Insight on the News*, a conservative magazine owned by Sun Myung Moon's Unification Church.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 1987, Gladwell began covering business and science for *The Washington Post*, where he worked until 1996.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In a personal elucidation of the 10,000-hour rule he popularized in *Outliers*, Gladwell notes, "I was a basket case at the beginning, and I felt like an expert at the end.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] When Gladwell started at *The New Yorker* in 1996, he wanted to "mine current academic research for insights, theories, direction, or inspiration".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His first assignment was to write a piece about fashion.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Instead of writing about high-class fashion, Gladwell opted to write a piece about a man who manufactured T-shirts, saying: "[I]t was much more interesting to write a piece about someone who made a T-shirt for $8 than it was to write about a dress that costs $100,000.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell gained popularity with two *New Yorker* articles, both written in 1996: "The Tipping Point" and "The Coolhunt".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] These two pieces would become the basis for Gladwell's first book, *The Tipping Point*, for which he received a $1 million advance.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He continues to write for *The New Yorker*.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell also was a contributing editor for *Grantland*, a sports journalism website founded by former ESPN columnist Bill Simmons.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] With the release of *Revenge of the Tipping Point: Overstories, Superspreaders, and the Rise of Social Engineering* in 2024, Gladwell has had eight books published.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] When asked for the process behind his writing, he said: "I have two parallel things I'm interested in.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] One is, I'm interested in collecting interesting stories, and the other is I'm interested in collecting interesting research.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The initial inspiration for his first book, *The Tipping Point*, which was published in 2000, came from the sudden drop of crime in New York City.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He wanted the book to have a broader appeal than just crime, however, and sought to explain similar phenomena through the lens of epidemiology.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] While Gladwell was a reporter for *The Washington Post*, he covered the AIDS epidemic.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He began to take note of "how strange epidemics were", saying epidemiologists have a "strikingly different way of looking at the world".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The term "tipping point" comes from the moment in an epidemic when the virus reaches critical mass and begins to spread at a much higher rate.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's theories of crime were heavily influenced by the "broken windows theory" of policing, and Gladwell is credited for packaging and popularizing the theory in a way that was implementable in New York City.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's theoretical implementation bears a striking resemblance to the "stop-and-frisk" policies of the NYPD.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] However, in the thirteen years since its publication, *The Tipping Point* and Gladwell have both come under fire for the tenuous link between "broken windows" and New York City's drop in violent crime.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] During a 2013 interview with BBC journalist Jon Ronson for *The Culture Show*, Gladwell admitted that he was "too in love with the broken-windows notion".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He went on to say that he was "so enamored by the metaphorical simplicity of that idea that I overstated its importance".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] After *The Tipping Point,* Gladwell published *Blink* in 2005.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The book attempts to explain how the human unconscious interprets events or cues as well as how past experiences can lead people to make informed decisions very rapidly.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell uses examples like the Getty kouros and psychologist John Gottman's research on the likelihood of divorce in married couples.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's hair was the inspiration for *Blink*.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He stated that once he allowed his hair to get longer, he started to get speeding tickets all the time, an oddity considering that he had never gotten one before and that he started getting pulled out of airport security lines for special attention.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In a particular incident, he was apprehended by three police officers while walking in downtown Manhattan because his curly hair matched the profile of a rapist, despite the fact the suspect looked nothing like him otherwise.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's *The Tipping Point* (2000) and *Blink* (2005) were international bestsellers.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] *The Tipping Point* sold more than two million copies in the United States.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] As of November 2008, the two books had sold a combined 4.5 million copies.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's third book, *Outliers*, published in 2008, examines how a person's environment, in conjunction with personal drive and motivation, affects his or her possibility and opportunity for success.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's original question revolved around lawyers: "We take it for granted that there's this guy in New York who's the corporate lawyer, right?
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] I just was curious: Why is it all the same guy?", referring to the fact that "a surprising number of the most powerful and successful corporate lawyers in New York City have almost the exact same biography".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In another example given in the book, Gladwell noticed that people ascribe Bill Gates's success to being "really smart" or "really ambitious".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He noted that he knew a lot of people who are really smart and really ambitious, but not worth $60 billion.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's fourth book, *What the Dog Saw: And Other Adventures*, was published in 2009.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] *What the Dog Saw* bundles together Gladwell's favourites of his articles from *The New Yorker* since he joined the magazine as a staff writer in 1996.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The stories share a common theme, namely that Gladwell tries to show us the world through the eyes of others, even if that other happens to be a dog.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's fifth book, *David and Goliath*, was released in October 2013, and examines the struggle of underdogs versus favourites.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The book is partially inspired by an article Gladwell wrote for *The New Yorker* in 2009 titled "How David Beats Goliath".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The book was a bestseller but received mixed reviews.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's sixth book, *Talking to Strangers*, was released September 2019.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The book examines interactions with strangers, covers examples that include the deceptions of Bernie Madoff, the trial of Amanda Knox, the suicide of Sylvia Plath, the Jerry Sandusky pedophilia case at Penn State, and the death of Sandra Bland.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's seventh book, *The Bomber Mafia: A Dream, a Temptation, and the Longest Night of the Second World War*, was released in April 2021.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's eighth book, *Revenge of the Tipping Point* was released in October 2024.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The book is a sequel commemorating the 25 year history of best selling first book, *The Tipping Point,* which was released in 2000.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The book discusses social epidemics and tipping points, this time with the aim of explaining the dark side of contagious phenomena, and offers an alternate history of two of the biggest epidemics of our day: COVID and the opioid crisis.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Reviewing *Blink*, *The Baltimore Sun* dubbed Gladwell "the most original American journalist since the young Tom Wolfe." Farhad Manjoo at *Salon* described the book as "a real pleasure.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] As in the best of Gladwell's work, *Blink* brims with surprising insights about our world and ourselves." *The Economist* called *Outliers* "a compelling read with an important message".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] David Leonhardt wrote in *The New York Times Book Review*: "In the vast world of nonfiction writing, Malcolm Gladwell is as close to a singular talent as exists today" and *Outliers* "leaves you mulling over its inventive theories for days afterward".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Ian Sample wrote in *The Guardian*: "Brought together, the pieces form a dazzling record of Gladwell's art.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2012, CBS's *60 Minutes* attributed the trend of American parents "redshirting" their five-year-olds (postponing entrance into kindergarten to give them an advantage) to a section in Gladwell's *Outliers*.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Sociology professor Shayne Lee referenced *Outliers* in a CNN editorial commemorating Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Lee discussed the strategic timing of King's ascent from a "Gladwellian perspective".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell gives credit to Richard Nisbett and Lee Ross for inventing the Gladwellian genre.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell's critics have described him as prone to oversimplification.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] *The New Republic* called the final chapter of *Outliers,* "impervious to all forms of critical thinking" and said Gladwell believes "a perfect anecdote proves a fatuous rule".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell has also been criticized for his emphasis on anecdotal evidence over research to support his conclusions.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Maureen Tkacik and Steven Pinker have challenged the integrity of Gladwell's approach.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Even while praising Gladwell's writing style and content, Pinker summed up Gladwell as "a minor genius who unwittingly demonstrates the hazards of statistical reasoning", while accusing him of "cherry-picked anecdotes, post-hoc sophistry and false dichotomies" in his book *Outliers*.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His approach was satirized by the online site "The Malcolm Gladwell Book Generator".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2005, Gladwell commanded a $45,000 speaking fee.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2008, he was making "about 30 speeches a year—most for tens of thousands of dollars, some for free", according to a profile in *New York* magazine.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2011, he gave three talks to groups of small businessmen as part of a three-city speaking tour put on by Bank of America.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The program was titled "Bank of America Small Business Speaker Series: A Conversation with Malcolm Gladwell".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Paul Starobin, writing in the *Columbia Journalism Review*, said the engagement's "entire point seemed to be to forge a public link between a tarnished brand (the bank), and a winning one (a journalist often described in profiles as the epitome of cool)".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] An article by Melissa Bell of *The Washington Post* posed the question: "Malcolm Gladwell: Bank of America's new spokesman?" *Mother Jones* editor Clara Jeffery said Gladwell's job for Bank of America had "terrible ethical optics".
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] However, Gladwell says he was unaware that Bank of America was "bragging about his speaking engagements" until the *Atlantic Wire* emailed him.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell has provided blurbs for "scores of book covers", leading *The New York Times* to ask, "Is it possible that Mr.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell has been spreading the love a bit too thinly?" Gladwell, who said he did not know how many blurbs he had written, acknowledged, "The more blurbs you give, the lower the value of the blurb.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell is host of the podcast *Revisionist History*, initially produced through Panoply Media and now through Gladwell's own podcast company.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] It began in 2016 and has aired seven 10-episode seasons.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Each episode begins with an inquiry about a person, event, or idea, and proceeds to question the received wisdom about the subject.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell was recruited to create a podcast by Jacob Weisberg, editor-in-chief of The Slate Group, which also includes the podcast network Panoply Media.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In September 2018, Gladwell announced he was co-founding a podcast company, later named Pushkin Industries, with Weisberg.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He also has a music podcast with Bruce Headlam and Rick Rubin, titled *Broken Record* where they interview musicians.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] It has two seasons, 2018–2019 and 2020 with a total of 49 episodes.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His family attended Above Bar Church in Southampton, U.K., and later Gale Presbyterian in Elmira when they moved to Canada.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His parents and siblings are part of the Mennonite community in Southwestern Ontario.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell wandered away from his Christian roots when he moved to New York, only to rediscover his faith while writing *David and Goliath* and his encounter with Wilma Derksen regarding the death of her child.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] Gladwell was a national class runner and an Ontario High School (Ontario Federation of School Athletic Associations – OFSAA) champion.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He was among Canada's fastest teenagers at 1500 metres, running 4:14 at the age of 13 and 4:05 when aged 14.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] At university, Gladwell ran 1500 metres in 3:55.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2014, at the age of 51, he ran a 4:54 at the Fifth Avenue Mile.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His first child, a daughter, was born in 2022.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2005, *Time* named Gladwell one of its 100 most influential people.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2007, he received the American Sociological Association's first Award for Excellence in the Reporting of Social Issues.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] The same year, he received an honorary degree from the University of Waterloo.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] In 2011, he was named a Member of the Order of Canada, the fifth highest honour for merit in the system of orders, decorations, and medals of Canada.
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] He has received honorary degrees from the University of Waterloo (2007) and the University of Toronto (2011).
[src:william-s-condon/malcolm-gladwell] His is a recipient of the 2024 Audio Vanguard Award presented by On Air Fest.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Gladwell describes the "three rules of epidemics" (or the three "agents of change") in the tipping points of epidemics.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] The Stickiness Factor refers to the specific content of a message that renders its impact memorable.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Popular children's television programs such as *Sesame Street* and *Blue's Clues* pioneered the properties of the stickiness factor, thus enhancing effective retention of educational content as well as entertainment value.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Gladwell states, "Kids don't watch when they are stimulated and look away when they are bored.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] They watch when they understand and look away when they are confused" (Gladwell, p.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Human behavior is sensitive to and strongly influenced by its environment.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Gladwell explains: "Epidemics are sensitive to the conditions and circumstances of the times and places in which they occur." For example, "zero tolerance" efforts to combat minor crimes such as farebeating and vandalism of the New York subway led to a decline in more violent crimes citywide.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Gladwell describes the bystander effect, and explains how Dunbar's number plays into the tipping point, using Rebecca Wells' novel *Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood*, evangelist John Wesley, and the high-tech firm W.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Gladwell also includes two chapters of case studies, situations in which tipping point concepts were used in specific situations.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] These situations include the athletic shoe company Airwalk, the diffusion model, how rumors are spread, decreasing the spread of syphilis in Baltimore, teen suicide in Micronesia, and teen smoking in the United States.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Gladwell received an estimated US$1–1.5 million advance for *The Tipping Point*, which sold 1.7 million copies by 2006.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] In the wake of the book's success, Gladwell was able to earn as much as $40,000 per lecture.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Sales increased again in 2006 after the release of Gladwell's next book, *Blink*.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] *The Guardian* ranked *The Tipping Point* #94 in its list of 100 Best Books of the 21st Century.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Some of Gladwell's analysis as to why the phenomenon of the "tipping point" occurs (particularly in relation to his idea of the "law of the few") and its unpredictable elements is based on the 1967 small-world experiment by social psychologist Stanley Milgram.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Milgram distributed letters to 160 students in Nebraska, with instructions that they be sent to a stockbroker in Boston (not personally known to them) by passing the letters to anyone else that they believed to be socially closer to the target.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] The study found that it took an average of six links to deliver each letter.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Of particular interest to Gladwell was the finding that just three friends of the stockbroker provided the final link for half of the letters that arrived successfully.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] This gave rise to Gladwell's theory that certain types of people are key to the dissemination of information.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] In 2003, Duncan Watts, a network theory physicist at Columbia University, repeated the Milgram study by using a web site to recruit 61,000 people to send messages to 18 targets worldwide.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] He successfully reproduced Milgram's results (the average length of the chain was approximately six links).
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] However, when he examined the pathways taken, he found that "hubs" (highly connected people) were not crucial.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Only 5% of the e-mail messages had passed through one of the hubs.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] This casts doubt on Gladwell's assertion that specific types of people are responsible for bringing about large levels of change.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Watts pointed out that if it were as simple as finding the individuals that can disseminate information prior to a marketing campaign, advertising agencies would presumably have a far higher success rate than they do.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] He also stated that Gladwell's theory does not square with much of his research into human social dynamics performed in the last ten years.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Economist Steven Levitt and Gladwell have a running dispute about whether the fall in New York City's crime rate can be attributed to the actions of the police department and "Fixing Broken Windows" (as claimed in *The Tipping Point*).
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] In *Freakonomics*, Levitt attributes the decrease in crime to two primary factors: 1) a drastic increase in the number of police officers trained and deployed on the streets and hiring Raymond W.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Kelly as police commissioner (thanks to the efforts of former mayor David Dinkins) and 2) a decrease in the number of unwanted children made possible by *Roe v.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] Wade*, causing crime to drop nationally in all major cities—"[e]ven in Los Angeles, a city notorious for bad policing".
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] And although psychologist Steven Pinker argues the second factor relies on tenuous links, recent evidence seems to uphold the likelihood of a significant causal link.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] A sequel was released in 2024, titled *Revenge of the Tipping Point*.
[src:william-s-condon/the-tipping-point] This book revisits Gladwell's previous work and retouches on some key ideas.
[src:william-s-condon/william-s-condon] In Canadian journalist Malcolm Gladwell's 2000 book, *The Tipping Point*, he cites Condon's research to help explain why some "Salesman" types may contribute more to word-of-mouth cultural 'epidemics'.
[src:william-s-condon/william-s-condon] Some other reference is made in Flora Davis's book "*Inside Intuition-What we know about Non-Verbal Communication*" published in New York by McGraw-Hill Books, which talks about the study he did on Interactional Syncrony.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Storytelling often involves improvisation or embellishment.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Stories or narratives have been shared in every culture as a means of entertainment, education, cultural preservation and in order to instill moral values.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] The earliest forms of storytelling were thought to have been primarily oral combined with gesture storytelling for many of the ancient cultures.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] The Australian Aboriginal people painted symbols from stories on cave walls as a means of helping the storyteller remember the story.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] The story was then told using a combination of oral narrative, music, rock art, and dance.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Traditionally, oral stories were committed to memory and then passed from generation to generation.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] However, in literate societies, written, televised, and internet media have largely replaced this method of communicating local, family, and cultural histories.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Oral storytelling remains the dominant medium of learning in some countries with low literacy rates.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Oral tradition (sometimes referred to as "oral culture" or "oral lore") is cultural material and traditions transmitted orally from one generation to another.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] The messages or testimony are verbally transmitted in speech or song and may take the form, for example, of folktales, sayings, ballads, songs, or chants.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] In this way, it is possible for a society to transmit oral history, oral literature, oral law and other knowledges across generations without a writing system.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Sociologists emphasize a requirement that the material is held in common by a group of people, over several generations, and thus distinguish oral tradition from testimony or oral history.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] In a general sense, "oral tradition" refers to the transmission of cultural material through vocal utterance, and was long held to be a key descriptor of folklore (a criterion no longer rigidly held by all folklorists).
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] As an academic discipline, it refers both to a set of objects of study and a method by which they are studied—the method may be called variously "oral traditional theory", "the theory of Oral-Formulaic Composition" and the "Parry-Lord theory" (after two of its founders).
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] The study of oral tradition is distinct from the academic discipline of oral history, which is the recording of personal memories and histories of those who experienced historical eras or events.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] It is also distinct from the study of orality, which can be defined as thought and its verbal expression in societies where the technologies of literacy (especially writing and print) are unfamiliar to most of the population.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Oral history is the recording of personal memories and histories of those who experienced historical eras or events.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Oral history is a method of historical documentation, using interviews with living survivors of the time being investigated.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Oral history often touches on topics scarcely touched on by written documents, and by doing so, fills in the gaps of records that make up early historical documents.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Oral history preservation is the field that deals with the care and upkeep of oral history materials, whatever format they may be in.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Verbal communication in the literal sense is oral communication with words that a person or other people speak out loud.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Social media is a form of electronic communication through which users create online communities to share information, ideas, personal messages, and other content (such as videos).
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Social media involves the way individuals communicate with others online.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Social media in itself is not word of mouth, but it is one way that word of mouth spreads.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] In fact, half of all word of mouth takes place online.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Practitioners have started using electronic word of mouth for consumer insight through text analytics, sentiment, hashtag analytics, and other machine learning tools.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] However, researchers of the Keller Fay Group found discussions are often face-to-face and not primarily dominated by social media.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Alluding to offline word of mouth (real life conversations) being just as persuasive as online word of mouth.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Researchers argue that social media itself is not word of mouth, but rather a medium through which word of mouth spreads.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Word of mouth is a story or verbal recommendation, as some researchers view social media as a mechanism.
[src:william-s-condon/word-of-mouth] Social media is thus a big part of how word of mouth travels between people.
